const CHEMISTRY_DATA = [

// ======================== CH1: MATTER ========================
{id:"ch1n1",topicId:"chem-ch1",type:"note",subtopic:"Matter and Its States",content:`Matter is anything that has mass and occupies space (has volume). It exists in three common states: SOLID (fixed shape and volume, particles tightly packed, strong intermolecular force, only vibrate about fixed positions), LIQUID (fixed volume but no fixed shape, particles loosely arranged, moderate force, can slide), GAS (no fixed shape or volume, particles far apart, negligible force, move freely at high speed). A fourth state, PLASMA (ionised gas, e.g. the Sun, lightning), and a fifth, BOSE-EINSTEIN CONDENSATE (near absolute zero), also exist.`,explanation:`Everything around you — your desk, water, air — is matter. The state depends on the balance between intermolecular FORCE OF ATTRACTION (which pulls particles together) and the KINETIC ENERGY of the particles (which pulls them apart).`,teacherTip:`Solid = ice cubes stacked tight. Liquid = water flowing. Gas = steam escaping. Plasma = a flame/lightning.`,examTip:`For each state, describe BOTH particle arrangement AND intermolecular force for full marks.`},
{id:"ch1n2",topicId:"chem-ch1",type:"note",subtopic:"Interconversion of States",content:`States of matter can change: Melting/Fusion (solid→liquid at melting point), Boiling/Vaporisation (liquid→gas at boiling point), Condensation (gas→liquid on cooling), Freezing/Solidification (liquid→solid on cooling), Sublimation (solid→gas directly), Deposition (gas→solid directly). KEY FACT: temperature remains CONSTANT during a change of state, because absorbed heat is used to overcome intermolecular forces, not to raise kinetic energy — this hidden heat is called LATENT HEAT.`,explanation:`Adding heat gives particles more energy to break free. Removing heat slows them down so they lock together again. During the change itself the thermometer "freezes" because energy goes into breaking bonds.`,teacherTip:`Draw the change-of-state cycle as a triangle: Solid ↔ Liquid ↔ Gas, with Sublimation/Deposition as the diagonal shortcut.`,examTip:`Always state that temperature remains CONSTANT during change of state AND name the reason: latent heat.`},
{id:"ch1n3",topicId:"chem-ch1",type:"note",subtopic:"Diffusion",content:`DIFFUSION is the spontaneous intermixing of particles of two substances due to their random (Brownian) motion, moving from a region of higher concentration to lower concentration. It occurs in gases (fastest), liquids (slower), and extremely slowly in solids. Example: smell of perfume spreading across a room; a drop of ink colouring a beaker of water.`,explanation:`Particles are always in random motion. When two substances meet, their particles intermingle on their own — no stirring needed. Higher temperature → faster particles → faster diffusion.`,teacherTip:`Diffusion is fastest in gases because gas particles move fastest and have the most empty space between them.`,examTip:`Rate of diffusion order: Gases > Liquids > Solids. Also state that rate INCREASES with temperature.`},
{id:"ch1n4",topicId:"chem-ch1",type:"note",subtopic:"NEET Bridge — Kinetic Theory & Gas Laws",content:`The "particles in random motion" idea you learn now becomes the KINETIC THEORY OF GASES in Class 11/NEET. Two results you should meet early: (1) average kinetic energy of gas particles ∝ absolute temperature (in Kelvin), and (2) Graham's Law of Diffusion — rate of diffusion is inversely proportional to the square root of molar mass: rate ∝ 1/√M. So a light gas (H₂) diffuses faster than a heavy gas (CO₂). Also note: 0°C = 273 K; to convert, K = °C + 273.`,explanation:`A lighter molecule moves faster at the same temperature, so it spreads faster. This single ratio (1/√M) is asked again and again in NEET diffusion problems.`,teacherTip:`Compare H₂ (M=2) and O₂ (M=32): H₂ diffuses √(32/2)=√16=4 times faster.`,examTip:`Olympiad/NEET: rate₁/rate₂ = √(M₂/M₁). Memorise the square-root, not the direct ratio.`},
// T/F
{id:"ch1tf1",topicId:"chem-ch1",type:"true_false",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"Gases have a definite shape and volume.",correctAnswer:"false",answer:`False. Gases have NEITHER a definite shape NOR a definite volume. They expand to completely fill any container.`,teacherTip:`Only solids have BOTH definite shape and volume.`,examTip:`Solids = both definite. Liquids = definite volume only. Gases = neither.`},
{id:"ch1tf2",topicId:"chem-ch1",type:"true_false",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"Diffusion is fastest in gases.",correctAnswer:"true",answer:`True. Gas particles have the highest kinetic energy and the largest intermolecular spaces, allowing them to intermix the fastest.`,teacherTip:`More space + more speed = faster mixing.`,examTip:`Compare diffusion rates across all three states when answering.`},
{id:"ch1tf3",topicId:"chem-ch1",type:"true_false",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"Temperature rises continuously while ice is melting at 0°C.",correctAnswer:"false",answer:`False. Temperature stays CONSTANT at 0°C until all the ice has melted. The heat supplied is used as latent heat to break the rigid solid structure, not to raise temperature.`,teacherTip:`During any change of state the thermometer "pauses".`,examTip:`Name the concept: latent heat of fusion.`},
// Fill blanks
{id:"ch1fb1",topicId:"chem-ch1",type:"fill_blank",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"The change of a solid directly into gas is called ______.",blankAnswer:"sublimation",answer:`Sublimation. Examples: camphor, dry ice (solid CO₂), naphthalene balls, ammonium chloride, iodine.`,teacherTip:`Sub-limation = the solid "skips" the liquid step.`,examTip:`Always give an example substance when mentioning sublimation.`},
{id:"ch1fb2",topicId:"chem-ch1",type:"fill_blank",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"The heat absorbed during change of state at constant temperature is called ______ heat.",blankAnswer:"latent",answer:`Latent heat — the "hidden" heat used to overcome intermolecular forces during melting or boiling, without changing temperature.`,teacherTip:`Latent = hidden. The energy is "hidden" because the thermometer shows no change.`,examTip:`Latent heat of FUSION (melting) and latent heat of VAPORISATION (boiling) are the two named types.`},
// MCQ
{id:"ch1mcq1",topicId:"chem-ch1",type:"mcq",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"Which state of matter has maximum intermolecular space?",options:["Solid","Liquid","Gas","Plasma"],correctOption:2,answer:`Gas. Particles in a gas are far apart with negligible attractive forces, which is why gases are highly compressible.`,teacherTip:`More space = easier to compress.`,examTip:`Link intermolecular space to compressibility in your answers.`},
{id:"ch1mcq2",topicId:"chem-ch1",type:"mcq",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"At the same temperature, which gas diffuses the fastest? (M = molar mass)",options:["CO₂ (M=44)","O₂ (M=32)","N₂ (M=28)","H₂ (M=2)"],correctOption:3,answer:`H₂. By Graham's Law, rate ∝ 1/√M. The lightest gas (smallest M) diffuses fastest.`,teacherTip:`Lightest = fastest. Use 1/√M.`,examTip:`Olympiad-style: rank by √M, then invert.`},
// Assertion-Reason (encoded as mcq)
{id:"ch1ar1",topicId:"chem-ch1",type:"mcq",subtopic:"Assertion–Reason",question:"Assertion (A): Gases can be compressed easily. Reason (R): Intermolecular spaces in gases are very large.",options:["Both A and R are true, and R is the correct explanation of A","Both A and R are true, but R is NOT the correct explanation of A","A is true but R is false","A is false but R is true"],correctOption:0,answer:`Both A and R are true, and R correctly explains A. Large intermolecular gaps allow particles to be pushed closer, so gases compress easily.`,teacherTip:`Compressibility is a direct consequence of empty space between particles.`,examTip:`NEET A-R format: first decide if each statement is independently true, THEN judge the link.`},
// Short answer
{id:"ch1sa1",topicId:"chem-ch1",type:"short_answer",subtopic:"Short/Long Answer",question:"Compare solids, liquids, and gases based on shape, volume, compressibility, and particle arrangement.",answer:`SOLIDS: Definite shape, definite volume, almost incompressible, particles tightly packed vibrating in fixed positions (strong force).\n\nLIQUIDS: No definite shape (takes container's shape), definite volume, slightly compressible, particles close but able to slide past each other (moderate force).\n\nGASES: No definite shape or volume, highly compressible, particles far apart moving randomly at high speed (negligible force).`,teacherTip:`Make a comparison table: Property | Solid | Liquid | Gas.`,examTip:`Compare at least 4 properties for maximum marks.`},
{id:"ch1sa2",topicId:"chem-ch1",type:"short_answer",subtopic:"HOTS / Application",question:"A naphthalene ball kept in a cupboard slowly disappears, while a piece of iron does not. Explain using the particle model.",answer:`Naphthalene undergoes SUBLIMATION — its molecules have relatively weak intermolecular forces, so at room temperature surface molecules gain enough energy to escape directly as vapour, and the ball slowly disappears (we also smell it, showing diffusion).\n\nIron has very strong metallic bonding between its particles; the energy available at room temperature is far too small for its particles to escape, so it does not sublime or noticeably diffuse.\n\nConclusion: whether a solid disappears depends on the strength of the forces holding its particles together.`,teacherTip:`Disappearing solid + smell = sublimation + diffusion working together.`,examTip:`Always tie the macroscopic observation back to intermolecular force strength.`},

// ======================== CH2: PHYSICAL AND CHEMICAL CHANGES ========================
{id:"ch2n1",topicId:"chem-ch2",type:"note",subtopic:"Physical vs Chemical Changes",content:`PHYSICAL CHANGE: A change in physical properties (shape, size, state) WITHOUT forming a new substance. Usually reversible. No change in chemical composition. No new energy bonds. Examples: melting ice, dissolving sugar, breaking glass, magnetising iron.\nCHEMICAL CHANGE (chemical reaction): A NEW substance is formed with different properties. Usually irreversible. Chemical bonds are broken and formed, so energy is absorbed or released. Examples: rusting iron, burning wood, cooking food, souring of milk, photosynthesis.`,explanation:`Tearing paper is physical (still paper). Burning paper is chemical (becomes ash + CO₂ + water vapour — completely new substances).`,teacherTip:`Physical = same substance, different look. Chemical = different substance entirely.`,examTip:`Give at least 4 differences with examples of each type.`},
{id:"ch2n2",topicId:"chem-ch2",type:"note",subtopic:"Signs of Chemical Change",content:`How to identify a chemical change (the 5 signs): (1) Change in COLOUR (iron turning rusty brown), (2) Evolution of GAS (bubbles when vinegar meets baking soda), (3) Change in TEMPERATURE — exothermic (heat released, e.g. burning, neutralisation) or endothermic (heat absorbed, e.g. cooking, electrolysis), (4) Formation of a PRECIPITATE (insoluble solid, e.g. AgCl), (5) Change in SMELL/STATE (milk turning sour). Often these are accompanied by light or sound (e.g. burning magnesium).`,explanation:`If you see bubbling, colour change, heat/light release, a precipitate, or a new smell — a chemical reaction is probably happening, because new substances are being formed.`,teacherTip:`Mnemonic: "Colour, Gas, Heat, Precipitate, Smell" — the 5 signs.`,examTip:`List at least 3 signs with a specific example each.`},
{id:"ch2n3",topicId:"chem-ch2",type:"note",subtopic:"NEET Bridge — Energy of Reactions",content:`Every chemical change is accompanied by an energy change because old bonds break (absorbs energy) and new bonds form (releases energy). If more energy is RELEASED than absorbed → EXOTHERMIC (e.g. combustion, respiration, neutralisation). If more is ABSORBED → ENDOTHERMIC (e.g. photosynthesis, thermal decomposition). In Class 11/NEET this becomes ENTHALPY change (ΔH): ΔH negative = exothermic, ΔH positive = endothermic.`,explanation:`A physical change has no bond breaking/forming, so its energy change is tiny and easily reversed; a chemical change reorganises bonds, which is why it usually cannot be reversed by simply removing heat.`,teacherTip:`Exo = "exit" (heat exits/leaves). Endo = "into" (heat goes in).`,examTip:`NEET: ΔH < 0 → exothermic, ΔH > 0 → endothermic.`},
// T/F
{id:"ch2tf1",topicId:"chem-ch2",type:"true_false",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"Melting of ice is a chemical change.",correctAnswer:"false",answer:`False. Melting of ice is a PHYSICAL change. Water changes state (solid→liquid) but its chemical composition (H₂O) is unchanged, and it is reversible by freezing.`,teacherTip:`Change of state = physical change. Always.`,examTip:`Mention "no new substance formed" and "reversible".`},
{id:"ch2tf2",topicId:"chem-ch2",type:"true_false",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"Rusting of iron is an irreversible chemical change.",correctAnswer:"true",answer:`True. Iron reacts with oxygen and moisture to form hydrated iron(III) oxide (rust, Fe₂O₃·xH₂O) — a completely new substance — and this cannot be easily reversed.`,teacherTip:`Rust ≈ Fe₂O₃·xH₂O (hydrated iron oxide), totally different from iron.`,examTip:`Name the product to show deeper understanding.`},
{id:"ch2tf3",topicId:"chem-ch2",type:"true_false",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"All chemical changes release heat.",correctAnswer:"false",answer:`False. Many chemical changes ABSORB heat (endothermic), e.g. photosynthesis and thermal decomposition of calcium carbonate. Only exothermic reactions release heat.`,teacherTip:`Not all reactions are exothermic — cooking absorbs heat.`,examTip:`Give one endothermic example to disprove "all".`},
// Fill blanks
{id:"ch2fb1",topicId:"chem-ch2",type:"fill_blank",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"A reaction that releases heat to the surroundings is called ______.",blankAnswer:"exothermic",answer:`Exothermic. Examples: combustion of fuels, respiration, neutralisation of an acid by a base.`,teacherTip:`Exo = heat exits.`,examTip:`Contrast with endothermic (absorbs heat).`},
// MCQ
{id:"ch2mcq1",topicId:"chem-ch2",type:"mcq",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"Which of the following is a chemical change?",options:["Dissolving sugar in water","Tearing paper","Burning magnesium ribbon","Melting butter"],correctOption:2,answer:`Burning magnesium ribbon produces magnesium oxide (white ash) — a new substance, with dazzling white light (exothermic). The others are physical changes.`,teacherTip:`Burning almost always = chemical change.`,examTip:`"Burning" and "rusting" are the most common exam examples.`},
{id:"ch2mcq2",topicId:"chem-ch2",type:"mcq",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"Souring of milk into curd is an example of a:",options:["Physical change, reversible","Chemical change, irreversible","Physical change, irreversible","Nuclear change"],correctOption:1,answer:`Chemical change that is irreversible — lactose is converted by bacteria into lactic acid (a new substance with a sour taste); curd cannot be turned back into milk.`,teacherTip:`New taste + cannot reverse = chemical & irreversible.`,examTip:`Curdling, fermentation and digestion are all chemical changes.`},
// Assertion-Reason
{id:"ch2ar1",topicId:"chem-ch2",type:"mcq",subtopic:"Assertion–Reason",question:"Assertion (A): Rusting of iron is a chemical change. Reason (R): A new substance with different properties is formed during rusting.",options:["Both A and R are true, and R is the correct explanation of A","Both A and R are true, but R is NOT the correct explanation of A","A is true but R is false","A is false but R is true"],correctOption:0,answer:`Both A and R are true and R explains A. Rust (hydrated iron oxide) is a new substance, which is exactly why rusting is classified as a chemical change.`,teacherTip:`The defining test of a chemical change is "new substance formed".`,examTip:`If R states the definition that justifies A, R is usually the correct explanation.`},
// Short answer
{id:"ch2sa1",topicId:"chem-ch2",type:"short_answer",subtopic:"Short/Long Answer",question:"Differentiate between physical and chemical changes. Give three examples of each.",answer:`PHYSICAL CHANGE:\n• No new substance formed\n• Usually reversible\n• No change in chemical composition\n• Little energy change\n• Examples: melting ice, dissolving salt, breaking a plate\n\nCHEMICAL CHANGE:\n• New substance with different properties is formed\n• Usually irreversible\n• Chemical composition changes\n• Significant energy change (heat/light)\n• Examples: burning wood, rusting iron, cooking an egg`,teacherTip:`The key question: "Is a NEW substance formed?" Yes = chemical. No = physical.`,examTip:`Compare at least 4 features and give 3 examples of each.`},
{id:"ch2sa2",topicId:"chem-ch2",type:"short_answer",subtopic:"HOTS / Application",question:"Burning of a candle involves both a physical and a chemical change. Justify this statement.",answer:`When a candle burns, two changes occur together:\n\nPHYSICAL CHANGE: The solid wax near the flame MELTS to liquid and some VAPORISES. This is only a change of state — the wax is still wax — and it is reversible (the liquid wax solidifies again on cooling).\n\nCHEMICAL CHANGE: The wax vapour BURNS in oxygen, producing carbon dioxide, water vapour, heat and light. These are new substances and the process is irreversible.\n\nHence candle burning is a classic example where a physical and a chemical change happen at the same time.`,teacherTip:`Melting wax = physical; burning vapour = chemical.`,examTip:`Always separate the two changes clearly with their reasons.`},

// ======================== CH3: ELEMENTS, COMPOUNDS AND MIXTURES ========================
{id:"ch3n1",topicId:"chem-ch3",type:"note",subtopic:"Elements, Compounds, Mixtures",content:`ELEMENT: A pure substance made of only one type of atom; cannot be broken down into simpler substances by chemical means. Examples: Iron (Fe), Oxygen (O₂), Gold (Au). About 118 known elements (≈92 natural). Elements are METALS (Fe, Cu, Na), NON-METALS (O, S, C) or METALLOIDS (Si, Ge).\nCOMPOUND: A pure substance of two or more elements CHEMICALLY combined in a FIXED ratio by mass. Properties differ from its elements. Examples: Water (H₂O), Salt (NaCl), CO₂.\nMIXTURE: Two or more substances PHYSICALLY mixed, NOT chemically combined, in ANY ratio; each keeps its own properties. Examples: air, salt water, salad.`,explanation:`Elements are like single Lego colours. Compounds are specific Lego models (fixed design, new properties). Mixtures are random piles of Lego (each piece keeps its identity).`,teacherTip:`Element = 1 type of atom. Compound = atoms chemically joined. Mixture = just physically mixed.`,examTip:`Key difference: compounds have a fixed ratio and chemical bonding; mixtures do not.`},
{id:"ch3n2",topicId:"chem-ch3",type:"note",subtopic:"Types of Mixtures",content:`HOMOGENEOUS MIXTURE (true solution): Uniform composition throughout; components NOT visible separately; particle size < 1 nm. Examples: salt water, air, brass (alloy). HETEROGENEOUS MIXTURE: Non-uniform; components visible/separable. Examples: sand+water, oil+water, salad. Borderline cases: a COLLOID (milk, fog — appears uniform but shows the Tyndall effect — scattering of light) and a SUSPENSION (muddy water — settles on standing).`,explanation:`In a homogeneous mixture, every sip of salt water tastes the same. In a heterogeneous mixture you can pick out the parts. A colloid is the tricky in-between case that scatters a light beam (Tyndall effect).`,teacherTip:`Homo = same throughout. Hetero = different parts visible.`,examTip:`Air is a homogeneous MIXTURE (not a compound!) — a very common exam trick.`},
{id:"ch3n3",topicId:"chem-ch3",type:"note",subtopic:"Separation of Mixtures",content:`Methods (each exploits ONE physical property difference): (1) FILTRATION — insoluble solid from liquid (sand/water) — by particle size. (2) EVAPORATION — dissolved solid from solution (salt/water) — by volatility. (3) DISTILLATION — miscible liquids with different boiling points (water from ink); FRACTIONAL DISTILLATION for close boiling points (petroleum, air). (4) MAGNETIC SEPARATION — magnetic solids (iron from sulphur). (5) CHROMATOGRAPHY — dyes/pigments by different rates of movement on paper. (6) SUBLIMATION — to separate a subliming solid (camphor from salt). (7) Separating FUNNEL — immiscible liquids (oil/water) by density. (8) CENTRIFUGATION — to separate fine suspended particles (cream from milk).`,explanation:`Match the method to the property difference: size→filtration, boiling point→distillation, magnetism→magnetic separation, density→separating funnel, solubility/adsorption→chromatography.`,teacherTip:`Always state the PROPERTY the method depends on.`,examTip:`Fractional distillation = liquids with CLOSE boiling points (uses a fractionating column).`},
// T/F
{id:"ch3tf1",topicId:"chem-ch3",type:"true_false",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"Air is a compound.",correctAnswer:"false",answer:`False. Air is a MIXTURE of gases (≈78% N₂, 21% O₂, plus CO₂, Ar, water vapour). Its components are not chemically bonded, have variable composition, and can be separated physically (by fractional distillation of liquid air).`,teacherTip:`Air = mixture. Water = compound. Don't confuse them!`,examTip:`Air has variable composition; compounds have fixed composition.`},
{id:"ch3tf2",topicId:"chem-ch3",type:"true_false",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"A compound can be separated into its elements by physical methods.",correctAnswer:"false",answer:`False. Compounds are broken into elements only by CHEMICAL methods (e.g. electrolysis, heating). Physical methods separate MIXTURES.`,teacherTip:`Physical separation = mixtures. Chemical separation = compounds.`,examTip:`Electrolysis of water (2H₂O → 2H₂ + O₂) is the classic chemical separation.`},
{id:"ch3tf3",topicId:"chem-ch3",type:"true_false",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"Milk is a true solution.",correctAnswer:"false",answer:`False. Milk is a COLLOID (an emulsion of fat in water). It appears uniform but scatters a beam of light (Tyndall effect), unlike a true solution.`,teacherTip:`If it shows the Tyndall effect, it's a colloid, not a true solution.`,examTip:`Colloid examples: milk, fog, blood, ink.`},
// Fill blanks
{id:"ch3fb1",topicId:"chem-ch3",type:"fill_blank",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"A mixture with uniform composition throughout is called a ______ mixture.",blankAnswer:"homogeneous",answer:`Homogeneous mixture (also called a solution). Every part has the same composition. Example: salt water, air.`,teacherTip:`Homo = same throughout.`,examTip:`Give an example alongside the term.`},
{id:"ch3fb2",topicId:"chem-ch3",type:"fill_blank",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"The scattering of a beam of light by a colloid is called the ______ effect.",blankAnswer:"Tyndall",answer:`The Tyndall effect — the scattering of light by colloidal particles, e.g. a beam of sunlight visible through fog or through gaps in trees.`,teacherTip:`Tyndall = the "torch beam in fog" test.`,examTip:`Used to distinguish a colloid from a true solution.`},
// MCQ
{id:"ch3mcq1",topicId:"chem-ch3",type:"mcq",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"Which method is used to separate salt from sea water?",options:["Filtration","Evaporation","Magnetic separation","Decantation"],correctOption:1,answer:`Evaporation. Heating sea water evaporates the water, leaving solid salt crystals behind.`,teacherTip:`Salt is dissolved (not suspended), so filtration won't work.`,examTip:`Filtration = insoluble solids; evaporation = dissolved solids.`},
{id:"ch3mcq2",topicId:"chem-ch3",type:"mcq",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"Two miscible liquids with very close boiling points are best separated by:",options:["Simple distillation","Fractional distillation","Filtration","Using a separating funnel"],correctOption:1,answer:`Fractional distillation — a fractionating column lets vapours repeatedly condense and evaporate, separating liquids whose boiling points are close (e.g. crude oil refining, separating O₂ and N₂ from liquid air).`,teacherTip:`CLOSE boiling points → you need the column → fractional.`,examTip:`Separating funnel is for IMMISCIBLE liquids only.`},
// Assertion-Reason
{id:"ch3ar1",topicId:"chem-ch3",type:"mcq",subtopic:"Assertion–Reason",question:"Assertion (A): The properties of water differ from those of hydrogen and oxygen. Reason (R): Water is a compound in which elements are chemically combined.",options:["Both A and R are true, and R is the correct explanation of A","Both A and R are true, but R is NOT the correct explanation of A","A is true but R is false","A is false but R is true"],correctOption:0,answer:`Both true and R explains A. In a compound, elements lose their individual properties because they are chemically bonded — so water (extinguishes fire) is unlike hydrogen (burns) and oxygen (supports burning).`,teacherTip:`Compounds = new properties; mixtures = retained properties.`,examTip:`This contrast (water vs H₂/O₂) is a favourite exam point.`},
// Short answer
{id:"ch3sa1",topicId:"chem-ch3",type:"short_answer",subtopic:"Short/Long Answer",question:"Differentiate between elements, compounds, and mixtures with examples.",answer:`ELEMENT: Made of one type of atom; cannot be decomposed chemically. Examples: Iron (Fe), Oxygen (O₂), Carbon (C).\n\nCOMPOUND: Two or more elements chemically combined in a FIXED ratio; properties differ from the constituent elements; separated only by chemical means. Examples: Water (H₂O), Carbon dioxide (CO₂).\n\nMIXTURE: Two or more substances physically mixed in ANY ratio; each retains its properties; separated by physical means. Examples: Air, salt water, sand + iron filings.`,teacherTip:`Element = simplest. Compound = chemically joined. Mixture = physically mixed.`,examTip:`Mention "fixed ratio" for compounds vs "any ratio" for mixtures.`},
{id:"ch3sa2",topicId:"chem-ch3",type:"short_answer",subtopic:"HOTS / Application",question:"You are given a mixture of common salt, sand and iron filings. Describe how you would obtain each component separately.",answer:`Step 1 — Remove IRON FILINGS by MAGNETIC SEPARATION: move a magnet over the mixture; iron filings cling to it. (Property used: magnetism.)\n\nStep 2 — Add WATER to the remaining salt + sand and stir. Salt DISSOLVES; sand does not.\n\nStep 3 — FILTER: sand stays as residue on the filter paper; salt solution passes through as filtrate. (Property used: difference in solubility/particle size.)\n\nStep 4 — EVAPORATE the salt solution: water evaporates, leaving pure salt crystals. (Property used: volatility.)\n\nResult: iron filings, sand and salt are recovered separately.`,teacherTip:`Always remove the magnetic solid FIRST, then use solubility.`,examTip:`State the property exploited at each step for full marks.`},

// ======================== CH4: ATOMIC STRUCTURE ========================
{id:"ch4n0",topicId:"chem-ch4",type:"note",subtopic:"Dalton's Atomic Theory",content:`John Dalton (1808) proposed the first scientific, rule-based model of the atom.\n\nKEY POSTULATES:\n(1) TINY PARTICLES — All matter is made up of very small particles called atoms.\n(2) INDIVISIBLE — Atoms cannot be divided, created, or destroyed during a chemical reaction.\n(3) IDENTICAL ELEMENTS — All atoms of a specific element are exactly alike in shape, size, and mass.\n(4) DIFFERENT ELEMENTS — Atoms of different elements have completely different sizes, masses, and properties.\n(5) SIMPLE RATIOS — Atoms combine in small, whole-number ratios (like 1:1 or 2:1) to form compounds.\n\nWHY IT IS IMPORTANT:\n• Mass Conservation — explains why total mass stays the same before and after a chemical reaction.\n• Foundation of Chemistry — the very first scientific, rule-based model of an atom.\n\nMODERN CORRECTIONS (for extra marks):\n• Divisible — atoms contain smaller particles: electrons, protons, and neutrons.\n• Isotopes — atoms of the same element can have slightly different masses (e.g. ¹²C and ¹⁴C).`,explanation:`Dalton gave chemistry its first atomic framework. Two postulates failed (indivisibility, identical atoms) but mass conservation and whole-number ratios still hold.`,teacherTip:`Learn the five postulates as a numbered list — examiners often ask "state Dalton's postulates".`,examTip:`Always add modern corrections: divisible (e, p, n) and isotopes (same element, different mass).`},
{id:"ch4n0b",topicId:"chem-ch4",type:"note",subtopic:"How Dalton Proposed His Model",content:`Dalton performed real experiments but could NOT see inside atoms. He studied gas behaviour and chemical reactions by weight.\n\n1. GAS EXPERIMENTS:\n• Compressed different gases in closed containers and mixed them.\n• Finding: each gas behaved independently — distinct individual particles.\n• Conclusion: air is made of tiny, hard, independent atoms moving and bouncing.\n\n2. WEIGHT EXPERIMENTS:\n• Measured exact masses when elements reacted (e.g. oxygen + nitric oxide over water).\n• Finding: a fixed mass of one element always combined with exactly 1 or 2 portions of another by weight.\n• Conclusion: Law of Multiple Proportions — whole-number ratios because matter is made of unbreakable blocks.\n\nSOLID SPHERE MODEL (Billiard Ball Model):\nDalton pictured atoms as tiny, hard, indivisible spheres (like marbles or billiard balls). In a reaction, atoms rearrange without breaking apart.`,explanation:`Gas experiments proved discrete particles; weight experiments proved whole-number combining ratios — together they built Dalton's theory.`,teacherTip:`Link the billiard-ball picture to postulate 2 (indivisible) — atoms only shuffle places in reactions.`,examTip:`"How did Dalton propose his theory?" = gas experiments + weight experiments + solid sphere model.`},
{id:"ch4n0c",topicId:"chem-ch4",type:"note",subtopic:"Comparison of Atomic Models — Master Table",content:`Compare Dalton, Thomson, Rutherford and Bohr at a glance:\n\n| Feature / Model | Dalton (1808) | Thomson (1904) | Rutherford (1911) | Bohr (1913) |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| **Common Name** | Billiard Ball / Solid Sphere | Plum Pudding / Watermelon | Nuclear / Planetary | Shell / Orbit Model |\n| **Main Concept** | Indivisible hard solid sphere; subatomic particles unknown | Positive sphere with electrons embedded | Mostly empty space; tiny dense nucleus | Electrons in fixed circular shells |\n| **Positive Charge** | Not defined (whole atom indivisible) | Uniformly throughout the sphere | Concentrated in nucleus | In the nucleus |\n| **Electrons** | Not discovered | Embedded in positive sphere | Revolve around nucleus (arbitrary paths) | Fixed shells K, L, M, N (n = 1, 2, 3, 4) |\n| **Electron Energy** | N/A | N/A | Continuous loss predicted → unstable | Fixed per shell; no radiation unless jumping shells |\n| **Major Limitation** | No subatomic particles; no isotopes | Failed alpha-scattering results | No stability explanation | Large multi-electron atoms / spectra |`,explanation:`Use this table for compare-and-contrast questions — each row is one exam marking point.`,teacherTip:`Thomson vs Rutherford: spread positive charge vs nucleus; pudding vs empty space.`,examTip:`Learn the Major Limitation row by heart — four models, four one-line drawbacks.`},
{id:"ch4n0d",topicId:"chem-ch4",type:"note",subtopic:"125-Year Detective Story — How the Atom Was Built",content:`Atomic structure was built step-by-step over ~125 years — each discovery exposed a flaw in the previous model.\n\n1. DALTON (1808) — Solid billiard-ball atom; indivisible. → Forced: can anything be extracted from inside?\n2. CROOKES (1878–79) — Cathode rays; atoms not fully solid.\n3. GOLDSTEIN (1886) — Canal rays; positive charge must exist too.\n4. THOMSON (1897) — Electron; Plum Pudding Model (1904). → Forced: how is charge really arranged?\n5. RUTHERFORD (1911) — Nucleus & proton; mostly empty space. → Forced: why don't electrons crash in?\n6. BOHR (1913) — Fixed shells K, L, M, N; stability solved. → Forced: why does nucleus mass exceed proton mass?\n7. CHADWICK (1932) — Neutron; nucleus = p + n, electrons in shells — blueprint complete.\n\n| Year | Discovery | Scientist | Impact | Forced Next |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| 1808 | Atom | Dalton | Basic building block | Test indivisibility |\n| 1897 | Electron | Thomson | Atom divisible; negative charge | Find positive balance |\n| 1911 | Nucleus & Proton | Rutherford | Positive core; empty space | Explain electron stability |\n| 1913 | Fixed Shells | Bohr | Stability crisis solved | Explain excess nuclear mass |\n| 1932 | Neutron | Chadwick | Neutral nuclear mass | Completed atom structure |`,explanation:`Chain of flaws drives progress — always link discovery → problem created → next scientist.`,teacherTip:`Ask after each step: "What puzzle did this leave unsolved?"`,examTip:`Memorise summary table years and "Forced Next" column for long answers.`},
{id:"ch4n1",topicId:"chem-ch4",type:"note",subtopic:"Structure of an Atom",content:`An atom has three subatomic particles: (1) PROTON — charge +1, in the nucleus, mass ≈ 1 u, discovered by Goldstein. (2) NEUTRON — no charge (neutral), in the nucleus, mass ≈ 1 u, discovered by Chadwick. (3) ELECTRON — charge −1, revolves around the nucleus in shells/energy levels, mass ≈ 1/1836 u (negligible), discovered by J.J. Thomson.\nAtomic Number (Z) = number of protons. Mass Number (A) = protons + neutrons. Neutrons = A − Z. In a neutral atom, protons = electrons.`,explanation:`The nucleus (centre) holds protons and neutrons and almost all the mass; electrons whizz around it. Rutherford's gold-foil experiment showed the nucleus is tiny, dense and positively charged.`,teacherTip:`Protons = Positive = in the Plus centre. Electrons = nEgative = outside.`,examTip:`Atoms are neutral: protons = electrons. Neutrons = A − Z.`},
{id:"ch4n1c",topicId:"chem-ch4",type:"note",subtopic:"J.J. Thomson's Cathode Ray Tube Experiment (1897)",content:`In 1897, J.J. Thomson discovered the electron via the Cathode Ray Tube (CRT) — proving Dalton's indivisible atom wrong.\n\nSETUP: Partially evacuated glass tube; cathode (−) and anode (+) with central hole; high voltage; ZnS fluorescent screen at the end.\n\nTHREE OBSERVATIONS:\n(1) Rays travel in straight lines (sharp shadows).\n(2) Electric field deflects beam toward positive plate; magnetic field also deflects it.\n(3) Same rays from any cathode metal or gas.\n\nCONCLUSIONS:\n• Negatively charged particles (corpuscles = electrons).\n• Fundamental part of ALL atoms.\n• Mass ≈ 1/1837 of hydrogen (very light).\n\nPLUM PUDDING MODEL (1904): Uniform positive sphere with electrons embedded — like raisins in a pudding.`,explanation:`Deflection toward + plate = negative charge. Same ray from every metal = electrons in all atoms.`,teacherTip:`CRT = old TV tube technology — real-world cathode rays.`,examTip:`State setup + 3 observations + 3 conclusions + plum pudding model for full marks.`},
{id:"ch4n1e",topicId:"chem-ch4",type:"note",subtopic:"Thomson's Charge-to-Mass Ratio (e/m)",content:`Thomson did NOT measure charge (e) or mass (m) directly — he found e/m. Millikan later found e; together they gave m.\n\nSTEP 1 — Balance E and B fields:\nF_E = e×E upward; F_B = e×v×B downward. When balanced: v = E/B.\n\nSTEP 2 — Bend beam with B only:\nMagnetic force curves path (radius r). e×v×B = m×v²/r → e/m = v/(B×r).\n\nSTEP 3 — Combine:\ne/m = E/(B²×r) ≈ 1.76×10¹¹ C/kg.\n\nSTEP 4 — Mass from Millikan's charge:\ne = 1.602×10⁻¹⁹ C (Millikan) → m = e÷(e/m) ≈ 9.1×10⁻³¹ kg (≈1/1837 of hydrogen).`,explanation:`Thomson gets the ratio; Millikan gets the charge; division gives electron mass.`,teacherTip:`Balance fields first (velocity), then bend (ratio), then Millikan (mass).`,examTip:`Quote e/m ≈ 1.76×10¹¹ C/kg and m ≈ 9.1×10⁻³¹ kg for NEET-style questions.`},
{id:"ch4n1f",topicId:"chem-ch4",type:"note",subtopic:"Millikan's Oil Drop Experiment (1909)",content:`In 1909, Robert Millikan found the electron's exact charge using the Oil Drop Experiment.\n\nSETUP: Atomizer (oil mist) + X-rays (charge drops negative) + two plates (+ top, − bottom) + microscope.\n\nSTEP 1 — Mass (plates OFF):\nDrop falls at terminal velocity v₁. F_g = m×g balances F_d (air resistance). Using oil density → find radius r → find mass m.\n\nSTEP 2 — Charge (plates ON):\nAdjust voltage until drop hovers. F_E = F_g → q×E = m×g → q = (m×g)/E.\n\nSTEP 3 — Quantization:\nThousands of drops showed q = whole number × 1.6×10⁻¹⁹ C. Smallest unit = one electron:\ne ≈ 1.602×10⁻¹⁹ C.\n\nWith Thomson's e/m, electron mass m ≈ 9.1×10⁻³¹ kg.`,explanation:`Free fall gives mass; hovering in E-field gives charge; whole-number multiples prove quantization.`,teacherTip:`Millikan + Thomson = complete electron: charge + mass.`,examTip:`e = 1.602×10⁻¹⁹ C and charge quantization are the key exam points.`},
{id:"ch4n1g",topicId:"chem-ch4",type:"note",subtopic:"Discovery of the Proton — Goldstein to Rutherford",content:`Two-part journey: Goldstein (1886) → canal rays; Rutherford (1919/1920) → proton named.\n\nSTEP 1 — GOLDSTEIN (1886):\nPerforated cathode tube. Faint rays travel opposite to cathode rays, through cathode holes → canal/anode rays.\nFormation: electrons hit gas atoms → positive ions → attracted to cathode → pass through holes.\n\nSTEP 2 — PROPERTIES:\n• Bend toward negative plate → positive charge.\n• Mass varies with gas used.\n• Hydrogen gives lightest positive particles.\n\nSTEP 3 — RUTHERFORD (1919):\nAlpha particles + nitrogen gas → oxygen + mystery particle.\nParticle = hydrogen nucleus = fundamental building block in all nuclei.\nNamed PROTON in 1920 (Greek protos = first).\n\nProton: charge +1, mass ≈1 u, symbol ₊₁p¹.`,explanation:`Canal rays showed positive particles exist; Rutherford proved the hydrogen nucleus is inside every atom.`,teacherTip:`Goldstein found canal rays; Rutherford isolated and named the proton — don't merge the two in exams.`,examTip:`Goldstein 1886 = canal rays. Rutherford 1919 = proton. H gas = lightest positive particles.`},
{id:"ch4n1h",topicId:"chem-ch4",type:"note",subtopic:"Discovery of the Neutron — Chadwick (1932)",content:`PUZZLE (1920s): Nucleus has protons, but mass ≈ double proton count. He nucleus: 2 protons, mass = 4 protons.\n\nJames Chadwick (Rutherford's student) → third particle needed: adds mass, zero charge.\n\nCHADWICK'S EXPERIMENT:\n(1) Bombardment — α particles on thin beryllium sheet.\n(2) Mysterious radiation — highly penetrating, unaffected by E/M fields → neutral.\n(3) Paraffin wax test — radiation knocks high-speed protons out of wax (rich in H).\n(4) Calculation — ejected proton speed/energy → particles ≈ proton mass.\n\nNamed NEUTRONS (₀n¹). Completed atom model (p + e + n). Nobel Prize 1935.\n\nNeutron: charge 0, mass ≈1 u (1.675×10⁻²⁷ kg). Hydrogen has no neutron.`,explanation:`α + Be → neutral rays → paraffin ejects protons → Chadwick proves neutron mass.`,teacherTip:`Four-step Chadwick story is a standard long-answer pattern.`,examTip:`Chadwick 1932. Paraffin wax + neutral radiation = key exam phrase.`},
{id:"ch4n1h2",topicId:"chem-ch4",type:"note",subtopic:"Chadwick's Neutron — Experiment & Mathematics",content:`WHOM/WHEN: James Chadwick, 1932 (Nobel 1935).\n\nWHY: He mass 2p but mass 4u; C has 6p but mass 12u. Rutherford (1920) predicted neutral nuclear particle — hard to detect (no E/M deflection).\n\nHOW (built on Joliot-Curie work):\nPolonium → α particles → beryllium target → neutral penetrating radiation → paraffin wax → protons knocked out → ionization chamber/oscilloscope measured velocity.\n\nREACTION: ⁴₂He + ⁹₄Be → ¹²₆C + ¹₀n\n\nMATH:\n(A) Gamma ruled out — need ~50 MeV photon but only ~14 MeV available → violates energy conservation → must be massive particle.\n(B) Elastic collision: v_max = [2mₙ/(mₙ+m)]×vₙ. Used H (m≈1) and N (m≈14) targets → vₙ cancels:\nv_p/v_N = (mₙ+14)/(mₙ+1)\n(C) Data: v_p=3.3×10⁷ m/s, v_N=4.7×10⁶ m/s → ratio 7.02 → mₙ≈1.16 u → refined mₙ≈1.008 u (≈1 amu).\n\nProved neutral particle ≈ proton mass = NEUTRON.`,explanation:`Energy budget kills gamma theory; dual-target collision math gives neutron mass without knowing vₙ.`,teacherTip:`14 MeV vs 50 MeV is the gamma-ray knockout argument.`,examTip:`Reaction + paraffin test + mₙ≈1 u are the three must-know points.`},
{id:"ch4n1i",topicId:"chem-ch4",type:"note",subtopic:"Comparison — Electron, Proton and Neutron",content:`| Property | Electron (e⁻) | Proton (p⁺) | Neutron (n) |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Discoverer | J.J. Thomson (1897) | Ernest Rutherford (1919) | James Chadwick (1932) |\n| Location | Outside nucleus (orbits) | Inside nucleus | Inside nucleus |\n| Absolute Charge | −1.6×10⁻¹⁹ C | +1.6×10⁻¹⁹ C | 0 |\n| Relative Charge | −1 | +1 | 0 |\n| Absolute Mass | 9.109×10⁻³¹ kg | 1.673×10⁻²⁷ kg | 1.675×10⁻²⁷ kg |\n| Relative Mass | 1/1837 u (≈0) | 1 u | 1 u |\n| Mass Comparison | Lightest (~1837× lighter) | ≈ H atom mass | Slightly heaviest |\n\nP-E-N: Proton +, Electron −, Neutron 0.`,explanation:`Electron negligible mass; proton and neutron carry nuclear mass.`,teacherTip:`Unaffected by fields → neutron.`,examTip:`Know discoverer + charge + location for each particle.`},
{id:"ch4n1j",topicId:"chem-ch4",type:"note",subtopic:"Thomson's CRT vs Goldstein's Canal Ray Tube",content:`| Feature | Thomson's CRT | Goldstein's Canal Ray Tube |\n|---|---|---|\n| Primary Discovery | Electron (e⁻) | Proton / positive ions (p⁺) |\n| Rays Produced | Cathode rays (electrons) | Canal/anode rays (positive gas ions) |\n| Cathode Design | Solid metal plate | Perforated cathode (tiny holes) |\n| Ray Direction | Cathode (−) → Anode (+) | From anode side, through cathode holes |\n| Charge | Negative | Positive |\n| Gas Dependence | Same rays regardless of gas | Mass and nature change with gas |\n| Particle Mass | Very light (1/1837 of H) | Heavy (≈ atomic mass of gas) |\n| Glow Location | Glass behind anode | Glass behind perforated cathode |\n\nThomson = solid cathode, negative, gas-independent. Goldstein = holes, positive, gas-dependent.`,explanation:`Two tubes, opposite rays — CRT finds electron; canal tube finds positive ions.`,teacherTip:`Don't swap glow positions — CRT behind anode; canal behind perforated cathode.`,examTip:`Perforated cathode + gas-dependent mass = Goldstein's tube.`},
{id:"ch4n1d",topicId:"chem-ch4",type:"note",subtopic:"William Crookes — Cathode Rays (1878)",content:`In 1878, Sir William Crookes discovered cathode rays using a highly evacuated Crookes Tube and high voltage.\n\nEXPERIMENT 1 — MALTESE CROSS:\n• Observation: Sharp shadow of cross on glowing glass.\n• Conclusion: Rays from cathode travel in straight lines → named cathode rays.\n\nEXPERIMENT 2 — PADDLE WHEEL:\n• Observation: Wheel spins and rolls toward anode.\n• Conclusion: Rays are material particles with mass and kinetic energy.\n\nEXPERIMENT 3 — MAGNETIC DEFLECTION:\n• Observation: Beam bends when magnet brought near.\n• Conclusion: Rays carry electrical charge.\n\nLINK TO THOMSON (1897): Crookes proved rays are straight, massive, charged particles. Thomson later measured e/m ratio and named them electrons.`,explanation:`Three Crookes experiments prove direction, mass, and charge — Thomson completes the story with the electron.`,teacherTip:`Cross = straight; wheel = mass; magnet = charge — one property per experiment.`,examTip:`Exam favourite: match each Crookes experiment to its conclusion.`},
{id:"ch4n1b",topicId:"chem-ch4",type:"note",subtopic:"Rutherford's Atomic Model",content:`In 1911, Lord Ernest Rutherford conducted the Alpha (α) Particle Scattering Experiment (Gold Foil Experiment). He bombarded a very thin gold foil (~1000 atoms thick) with fast-moving, positively charged alpha particles, using a circular fluorescent screen to detect where they hit.\n\nKEY OBSERVATIONS: (1) Most alpha particles passed straight through without deviation. (2) A few were deflected by small angles. (3) About 1 in 12,000 rebounded completely (180°).\n\nCONCLUSIONS: (1) Most of the atom is EMPTY SPACE. (2) A positively charged CENTRE exists (repels positive α particles). (3) This centre is extremely small, dense and heavy — the NUCLEUS.\n\nRUTHERFORD'S MODEL (Nuclear/Planetary Model): (1) NUCLEUS — dense, positively charged centre; almost all mass is here. (2) ELECTRONS revolve around the nucleus in fixed circular orbits (like planets around the sun). (3) Atom is electrically NEUTRAL (electrons = protons in charge). (4) Nucleus is extremely SMALL compared to the atom.\n\nDRAWBACK: Classical physics says orbiting electrons must radiate energy and spiral into the nucleus — yet atoms are stable. Rutherford could not explain this (later solved by Bohr).`,explanation:`Three observations map to three conclusions: straight through → empty space; small deflections → positive centre; 180° rebound → tiny dense nucleus. The planetary model works visually but fails on stability.`,teacherTip:`Stadium-and-cricket-ball analogy: if the atom is a stadium, the nucleus is a cricket ball at the centre.`,examTip:`Alpha scattering discovered the NUCLEUS — not the proton or neutron. Know all three observations with their conclusions.`},
{id:"ch4n2",topicId:"chem-ch4",type:"note",subtopic:"Electron Shells and Valency",content:`Electrons fill shells (K, L, M, N…) following the BOHR-BURY rule. Maximum electrons in a shell = 2n² (K=2, L=8, M=18, N=32). BUT the outermost shell can never hold more than 8 (octet), and for the first 20 elements the filling pattern is 2, 8, 8, 2. The outermost electrons are VALENCE ELECTRONS. VALENCY = combining capacity = electrons gained, lost or shared to complete the octet (the octet rule: atoms tend to get 8 electrons in the outer shell; the K shell is "happy" with 2 — the duplet, e.g. He).`,explanation:`Sodium (2,8,1) has 1 valence electron and loses it, so valency = 1. Chlorine (2,8,7) needs 1 more electron, so valency = 1. Magnesium (2,8,2) loses 2, valency = 2.`,teacherTip:`Shell capacity = 2n². But outermost ≤ 8.`,examTip:`Draw dot-cross (electron) diagrams for at least 5 common elements.`},
{id:"ch4n3",topicId:"chem-ch4",type:"note",subtopic:"Isotopes and Isobars",content:`ISOTOPES: Atoms of the SAME element — same atomic number Z but DIFFERENT mass number A (different neutron count). Example: ¹²C and ¹⁴C (both Z=6, but 6 vs 8 neutrons); protium ¹H, deuterium ²H, tritium ³H. Isotopes have IDENTICAL chemical properties (same valence electrons) but slightly different physical properties.\nISOBARS: Atoms of DIFFERENT elements with the SAME mass number A but different Z. Example: ⁴⁰Ar (Z=18) and ⁴⁰Ca (Z=20).\nISOTONES: Atoms with the SAME number of neutrons. Example: ¹⁴C and ¹⁶O (both 8 neutrons).`,explanation:`Isotopes are like siblings — same family (element) but different weight. Isobars are strangers who happen to weigh the same.`,teacherTip:`Iso-TOPE = same Place (same element, same Z). Iso-BAR = same mass (same A).`,examTip:`Know examples: C-12/C-14, H-1/H-2/H-3; isobars ⁴⁰Ar/⁴⁰Ca.`},
{id:"ch4n4",topicId:"chem-ch4",type:"note",subtopic:"NEET Bridge — Models & Quantum Leap",content:`The shell model you use now is BOHR'S model (electrons in fixed circular orbits/energy levels). It improves on THOMSON's "plum-pudding" model and RUTHERFORD's nuclear model. In Class 11/NEET this evolves into the QUANTUM-MECHANICAL model: shells split into SUBSHELLS (s, p, d, f) and electrons fill them by increasing energy (Aufbau principle), Pauli's exclusion principle, and Hund's rule. The "2, 8, 18, 32 = 2n²" capacity comes directly from the number of subshell orbitals. Average atomic mass = weighted average of isotope masses (e.g. chlorine ≈ 35.5 because of ³⁵Cl and ³⁷Cl in ~3:1 ratio).`,explanation:`Class 8 gives you the picture (orbits/shells); NEET refines it into probability clouds (orbitals) and exact filling order. The 2n² rule is your bridge to the subshell counting later.`,teacherTip:`Cl's fractional mass (35.5) is the classic isotope-averaging question.`,examTip:`NEET: order of subshell energy follows the (n+l) rule — meet it early.`},
// T/F
{id:"ch4tf1",topicId:"chem-ch4",type:"true_false",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"The number of neutrons is always equal to the number of protons in an atom.",correctAnswer:"false",answer:`False. Neutrons = Mass number − Atomic number, and this often differs from the proton count (e.g. ²³Na has 11 protons but 12 neutrons). Only in light atoms like ¹²C are they sometimes equal.`,teacherTip:`Neutrons = A − Z, computed each time.`,examTip:`Never assume protons = neutrons.`},
{id:"ch4tf2",topicId:"chem-ch4",type:"true_false",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"Isotopes of an element have the same chemical properties.",correctAnswer:"true",answer:`True. Isotopes have the same number of valence electrons (same Z), so their chemical behaviour is identical; only physical properties (like mass/density) differ slightly.`,teacherTip:`Chemistry depends on electrons, which isotopes share.`,examTip:`Same Z → same valency → same chemistry.`},
// Fill blanks
{id:"ch4fb1",topicId:"chem-ch4",type:"fill_blank",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"The number of protons in an atom is called its ______.",blankAnswer:"atomic number",answer:`Atomic number (Z) = number of protons. It defines the identity of the element.`,teacherTip:`Change the protons = change the element.`,examTip:`In a neutral atom: atomic number = protons = electrons.`},
{id:"ch4fb2",topicId:"chem-ch4",type:"fill_blank",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"The maximum number of electrons a shell can hold is given by the formula ______.",blankAnswer:"2n²",answer:`2n², where n is the shell number (K n=1 → 2, L n=2 → 8, M n=3 → 18, N n=4 → 32). The outermost shell, however, cannot exceed 8.`,teacherTip:`2n² gives capacity; "outermost ≤ 8" is the extra rule.`,examTip:`State BOTH the 2n² rule and the octet limit.`},
// MCQ
{id:"ch4mcq1",topicId:"chem-ch4",type:"mcq",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"Isotopes have the same:",options:["Mass number","Number of neutrons","Atomic number","Density"],correctOption:2,answer:`Atomic number (same number of protons → same element) but different mass numbers (different neutrons).`,teacherTip:`Same element = same protons = same Z.`,examTip:`Isotopes differ ONLY in neutron count.`},
{id:"ch4mcq2",topicId:"chem-ch4",type:"mcq",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"An ion X²⁺ has 10 electrons and a mass number of 26. The number of protons and neutrons respectively are:",options:["10 and 16","12 and 12","12 and 14","10 and 14"],correctOption:2,answer:`Step 1 — Protons: a 2+ ion has LOST 2 electrons, so protons = electrons + 2 = 10 + 2 = 12 (the element is magnesium, Mg²⁺).\nStep 2 — Neutrons = mass number − protons = 26 − 12 = 14.\nSo protons = 12 and neutrons = 14.`,teacherTip:`For a cation Xⁿ⁺: protons = electrons + n.`,examTip:`Charge tells you electrons lost/gained; the element fixes the proton number.`},
// Assertion-Reason
{id:"ch4ar1",topicId:"chem-ch4",type:"mcq",subtopic:"Assertion–Reason",question:"Assertion (A): The valency of sodium is 1. Reason (R): A sodium atom has one electron in its outermost shell which it loses to attain a stable octet.",options:["Both A and R are true, and R is the correct explanation of A","Both A and R are true, but R is NOT the correct explanation of A","A is true but R is false","A is false but R is true"],correctOption:0,answer:`Both true and R explains A. Na is 2,8,1; losing the single outer electron gives the stable 2,8 configuration, so its combining capacity (valency) is 1.`,teacherTip:`Valency comes straight from the octet rule.`,examTip:`Link valency to "electrons lost/gained/shared to complete the octet".`},
// Short answer
{id:"ch4sa1",topicId:"chem-ch4",type:"short_answer",subtopic:"Short/Long Answer",question:"Draw the atomic structure of Sodium (Na, Z=11, A=23). State its valency.",answer:`Sodium (Na): Atomic number = 11, Mass number = 23\nProtons = 11, Neutrons = 23 − 11 = 12, Electrons = 11\n\nElectron arrangement: K(2), L(8), M(1)\n\nValency = 1 (it has 1 electron in the outermost shell, which it easily loses to attain the stable configuration 2,8).\n\nSodium is a metal and forms the Na⁺ ion by losing 1 electron.`,teacherTip:`Always calculate: Neutrons = Mass number − Atomic number.`,examTip:`Show the electron configuration AND justify the valency.`},
{id:"ch4sa2",topicId:"chem-ch4",type:"short_answer",subtopic:"HOTS / Application",question:"Chlorine has two isotopes, ³⁵Cl and ³⁷Cl, present in the ratio 3:1. Explain why the atomic mass of chlorine is written as 35.5 u.",answer:`Both isotopes are chlorine (Z=17) but have different mass numbers due to different neutron counts (18 and 20 neutrons).\n\nThe atomic mass listed in the periodic table is the WEIGHTED AVERAGE of the isotope masses, in proportion to their natural abundance:\n\nAverage mass = (35 × 3 + 37 × 1) / (3 + 1)\n            = (105 + 37) / 4\n            = 142 / 4\n            = 35.5 u\n\nThat is why chlorine's atomic mass is a fraction (35.5), even though individual atoms have whole-number mass numbers.`,teacherTip:`No single Cl atom weighs 35.5 — it is an average.`,examTip:`Weighted average = Σ(mass × fraction). A frequent NEET/Olympiad calculation.`},
{id:"ch4sa3",topicId:"chem-ch4",type:"short_answer",subtopic:"Short/Long Answer",question:"Describe Rutherford's Alpha (α) Particle Scattering Experiment. State the key observations, conclusions, main features of his atomic model, and its major drawback.",answer:`**1. Gold Foil Experiment (1911):** Rutherford bombarded a very thin gold foil with fast-moving, positively charged alpha (α) particles. A circular fluorescent screen detected where particles hit after passing through.\n\n**2. Key Observations:** (a) Most α particles passed straight through. (b) A few were deflected by small angles. (c) About 1 in 12,000 rebounded through 180°.\n\n**3. Conclusions:** (a) Most of the atom is empty space. (b) A positively charged centre exists (repels α particles). (c) This centre is extremely small, dense and heavy — the nucleus.\n\n**4. Rutherford's Model:** (a) Nucleus — dense, positive, holds almost all mass. (b) Electrons revolve in fixed circular orbits (planetary model). (c) Atom is electrically neutral. (d) Nucleus is tiny compared to the atom.\n\n**5. Drawback:** Orbiting electrons should radiate energy and spiral into the nucleus (classical physics), making atoms unstable — but atoms are stable. Rutherford could not explain this.`,teacherTip:`Learn observations and conclusions as matched pairs — examiners love this sequence.`,examTip:`Draw the apparatus (source, foil, screen) and state all three observations with conclusions for full marks.`},
{id:"ch4sa4",topicId:"chem-ch4",type:"short_answer",subtopic:"Short/Long Answer",question:"State the key postulates of Dalton's Atomic Theory. Why is it important? Which postulates were later proven incorrect?",answer:`**KEY POSTULATES (1808):**\n(1) Tiny Particles — all matter is made of very small particles called atoms.\n(2) Indivisible — atoms cannot be divided, created, or destroyed in a chemical reaction.\n(3) Identical Elements — all atoms of a specific element are alike in shape, size, and mass.\n(4) Different Elements — atoms of different elements differ in size, mass, and properties.\n(5) Simple Ratios — atoms combine in small whole-number ratios (1:1, 2:1, etc.) to form compounds.\n\n**WHY IMPORTANT:**\n• Mass Conservation — total mass stays the same before and after a reaction.\n• Foundation of Chemistry — first scientific, rule-based atomic model.\n\n**MODERN CORRECTIONS:**\n• Divisible — atoms contain electrons, protons, and neutrons.\n• Isotopes — atoms of the same element can differ in mass (e.g. ¹²C vs ¹⁴C).`,teacherTip:`Number your postulates clearly — full marks need all five plus corrections.`,examTip:`Link isotopes directly to postulate 3 (identical atoms) to score the "modern corrections" mark.`},
{id:"ch4sa5",topicId:"chem-ch4",type:"short_answer",subtopic:"Short/Long Answer",question:"How did John Dalton propose his atomic model? Describe his gas experiments, weight experiments, and the Solid Sphere (Billiard Ball) Model.",answer:`Dalton could not see inside atoms. He used experiments on gases and reacting weights:\n\n**GAS EXPERIMENTS:** He compressed and mixed gases in closed containers. Each gas behaved independently — as separate particles. Conclusion: air is made of tiny, hard atoms moving and bouncing.\n\n**WEIGHT EXPERIMENTS:** He measured masses when elements reacted (e.g. oxygen + nitric oxide). A fixed mass of one element always combined with exactly 1 or 2 portions of another by weight. Conclusion: Law of Multiple Proportions — whole-number ratios because matter is made of unbreakable blocks.\n\n**SOLID SPHERE MODEL:** Atoms are tiny, hard, indivisible spheres (billiard balls). In reactions, atoms rearrange without breaking apart.`,teacherTip:`Connect gas experiments → discrete particles; weight experiments → whole-number ratios.`,examTip:`Mention both experiment types AND the billiard-ball model for a complete answer.`},
{id:"ch4sa6",topicId:"chem-ch4",type:"short_answer",subtopic:"Short/Long Answer",question:"Describe J.J. Thomson's Cathode Ray Tube experiment (1897). State the setup, observations, conclusions, and the Plum Pudding Model.",answer:`**Setup:** Partially evacuated CRT with cathode (−), anode (+) with hole, high voltage, and ZnS fluorescent screen.\n\n**Observations:** (1) Rays travel straight. (2) Electric field bends beam toward positive plate; magnet also deflects it. (3) Same rays from any metal or gas.\n\n**Conclusions:** (1) Negatively charged electrons (corpuscles). (2) Present in all atoms. (3) Mass ≈ 1/1837 of hydrogen.\n\n**Plum Pudding Model (1904):** Uniform positive sphere with embedded electrons — disproved Dalton's indivisible atom.`,teacherTip:`Link electric deflection → negative charge → electron discovery.`,examTip:`Include ZnS screen, three observations, and plum pudding for full marks.`},
{id:"ch4sa7",topicId:"chem-ch4",type:"short_answer",subtopic:"Short/Long Answer",question:"Describe William Crookes' three experiments on cathode rays. State the observation and conclusion of each, and explain how this led to Thomson's discovery of the electron.",answer:`**Maltese Cross:** Sharp shadow on glowing glass → rays travel in straight lines from the cathode (cathode rays).\n\n**Paddle Wheel:** Wheel spins toward anode → rays are material particles with mass and kinetic energy.\n\n**Magnetic Deflection:** Beam bends near a magnet → rays carry electrical charge.\n\n**Thomson (1897):** Used the Crookes Tube, measured e/m ratio, proved particles are ~1/1837 mass of hydrogen, and named them electrons.`,teacherTip:`One experiment = one property: cross (straight), wheel (mass), magnet (charge).`,examTip:`Always state observation AND conclusion for each Crookes experiment.`},

// ======================== CH5: LANGUAGE OF CHEMISTRY ========================
{id:"ch5n1",topicId:"chem-ch5",type:"note",subtopic:"Symbols, Formulae, Equations",content:`CHEMICAL SYMBOL: A short abbreviation for an element (1 or 2 letters; first always capital, second always small). Examples: H, Na, Fe. Many come from Latin: Na (Natrium), K (Kalium), Fe (Ferrum), Cu (Cuprum), Ag (Argentum), Au (Aurum), Pb (Plumbum), Sn (Stannum).\nCHEMICAL FORMULA: Shows the kinds and numbers of atoms in a molecule using symbols and subscripts; H₂O = 2 H + 1 O. The formula of an ionic compound is found by the CRISS-CROSS (valency) method.\nCHEMICAL EQUATION: Represents a reaction (Reactants → Products) and must be BALANCED (equal atoms of each element on both sides) to obey the Law of Conservation of Mass.`,explanation:`Symbols are abbreviations (Dr. for Doctor). Formulae are molecular recipes. Equations are cooking instructions showing inputs and outputs.`,teacherTip:`Learn the Latin-origin symbols separately — they are easy marks.`,examTip:`In the criss-cross method, the valency of one ion becomes the subscript of the other.`},
{id:"ch5n2",topicId:"chem-ch5",type:"note",subtopic:"Balancing Chemical Equations",content:`A balanced equation has equal numbers of each atom on both sides (Law of Conservation of Mass — matter is neither created nor destroyed in a chemical reaction). Steps: (1) Write the word equation. (2) Write the unbalanced equation with correct formulae. (3) Count atoms of each element on both sides. (4) Add COEFFICIENTS (never change subscripts) to balance, often using the LCM. (5) Verify. Add STATE SYMBOLS: (s) solid, (l) liquid, (g) gas, (aq) aqueous. Example: 2H₂(g) + O₂(g) → 2H₂O(l).`,explanation:`If you start with 4 H atoms and 2 O atoms you must end with the same. Atoms are only rearranged — nothing disappears.`,teacherTip:`Never change subscripts to balance! Only change coefficients (the big numbers in front).`,examTip:`Always verify by counting atoms on both sides, and add state symbols where asked.`},
{id:"ch5n3",topicId:"chem-ch5",type:"note",subtopic:"NEET Bridge — Radicals, Valency & the Mole",content:`A RADICAL (ion) is a charged group of atoms acting as a unit: sulphate SO₄²⁻, carbonate CO₃²⁻, nitrate NO₃⁻, ammonium NH₄⁺, hydroxide OH⁻. Learn their valencies — they let you build formulae fast by criss-cross. In Class 11/NEET, balanced equations become STOICHIOMETRY: coefficients give MOLE RATIOS, and 1 mole = 6.022 × 10²³ particles (Avogadro's number) = the gram molecular mass of a substance. So "2H₂ + O₂ → 2H₂O" reads as "2 moles H₂ react with 1 mole O₂".`,explanation:`The coefficients you balance now are exactly the mole ratios you will use to calculate masses and volumes in NEET. Memorising common radical valencies makes both formula-writing and balancing far faster.`,teacherTip:`Memorise the common radicals table early — it pays off for years.`,examTip:`NEET: coefficients = mole ratio; 1 mole = 6.022 × 10²³ particles.`},
// T/F
{id:"ch5tf1",topicId:"chem-ch5",type:"true_false",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"The symbol for Sodium is So.",correctAnswer:"false",answer:`False. The symbol for sodium is Na (from the Latin Natrium). Symbols are 1 or 2 letters with only the first capitalised.`,teacherTip:`Na = Natrium (Latin for sodium).`,examTip:`Latin symbols: Na, K, Fe, Cu, Ag, Au, Pb, Sn, Hg.`},
{id:"ch5tf2",topicId:"chem-ch5",type:"true_false",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"To balance an equation, you may change the subscripts in a formula.",correctAnswer:"false",answer:`False. NEVER change subscripts — that would change the substance itself. Balance only by placing COEFFICIENTS in front of formulae.`,teacherTip:`Subscripts define the substance; coefficients count molecules.`,examTip:`Changing H₂O to H₂O₂ makes a totally different compound (hydrogen peroxide).`},
// Fill blanks
{id:"ch5fb1",topicId:"chem-ch5",type:"fill_blank",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"The formula of water is ______.",blankAnswer:"H₂O",answer:`H₂O — each water molecule contains 2 hydrogen atoms and 1 oxygen atom.`,teacherTip:`The subscript 2 means 2 atoms of hydrogen; no subscript = 1 atom.`,examTip:`Know formulae of common compounds: H₂O, CO₂, NaCl, HCl, H₂SO₄, NaOH, CaCO₃.`},
{id:"ch5fb2",topicId:"chem-ch5",type:"fill_blank",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"A charged group of atoms that behaves as a single unit is called a ______.",blankAnswer:"radical",answer:`A radical (polyatomic ion), e.g. sulphate SO₄²⁻, carbonate CO₃²⁻, ammonium NH₄⁺.`,teacherTip:`Radicals stay together through a reaction.`,examTip:`Learn radical valencies for the criss-cross method.`},
// MCQ
{id:"ch5mcq1",topicId:"chem-ch5",type:"mcq",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"In a balanced chemical equation, what is conserved?",options:["Colour","Volume","Mass (number of atoms)","Temperature"],correctOption:2,answer:`Mass is conserved (Law of Conservation of Mass): the total number of atoms of each element is equal on both sides.`,teacherTip:`Atoms are rearranged, not created or destroyed.`,examTip:`Name the law for extra marks.`},
{id:"ch5mcq2",topicId:"chem-ch5",type:"mcq",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"The correct formula of aluminium sulphate (Al valency 3, sulphate valency 2) is:",options:["AlSO₄","Al₂SO₄","Al₂(SO₄)₃","Al₃(SO₄)₂"],correctOption:2,answer:`Al₂(SO₄)₃. By criss-cross, Al's valency 3 becomes the subscript of sulphate and sulphate's valency 2 becomes the subscript of Al, giving Al₂(SO₄)₃.`,teacherTip:`Criss-cross the valencies; bracket the radical before adding a subscript.`,examTip:`Always put a polyatomic radical in brackets when it needs a subscript >1.`},
// Assertion-Reason
{id:"ch5ar1",topicId:"chem-ch5",type:"mcq",subtopic:"Assertion–Reason",question:"Assertion (A): A chemical equation must be balanced. Reason (R): Matter can be created during a chemical reaction.",options:["Both A and R are true, and R is the correct explanation of A","Both A and R are true, but R is NOT the correct explanation of A","A is true but R is false","A is false but R is true"],correctOption:2,answer:`A is true but R is false. Equations are balanced PRECISELY because matter is NOT created or destroyed (Law of Conservation of Mass). R states the opposite of the truth.`,teacherTip:`Watch for a reason that contradicts the law it should support.`,examTip:`A correct assertion can pair with a false reason — read both independently.`},
// Short answer
{id:"ch5sa1",topicId:"chem-ch5",type:"short_answer",subtopic:"Short/Long Answer",question:"Balance the following equation: Fe + O₂ → Fe₂O₃",answer:`Step 1 — Count atoms:\nLeft: Fe = 1, O = 2 | Right: Fe = 2, O = 3\n\nStep 2 — Balance Fe (put 2 before Fe):\n2Fe + O₂ → Fe₂O₃  (Fe balanced; O still unbalanced)\n\nStep 3 — Balance O using LCM of 2 and 3 = 6:\n4Fe + 3O₂ → 2Fe₂O₃\n\nCheck: Left: Fe = 4, O = 6 | Right: Fe = 4, O = 6 ✓\n\nBalanced equation: 4Fe + 3O₂ → 2Fe₂O₃`,teacherTip:`Find the LCM when oxygen atoms don't balance easily.`,examTip:`Always show the verification step.`},
{id:"ch5sa2",topicId:"chem-ch5",type:"short_answer",subtopic:"HOTS / Application",question:"Write the balanced equation, with state symbols, for the action of dilute sulphuric acid on zinc, and name the type of reaction.",answer:`Word equation: zinc + dilute sulphuric acid → zinc sulphate + hydrogen\n\nBalanced equation with state symbols:\nZn(s) + H₂SO₄(aq) → ZnSO₄(aq) + H₂(g)↑\n\nCheck: Zn 1=1, H 2=2, S 1=1, O 4=4 ✓\n\nType of reaction: a DISPLACEMENT reaction (zinc, being more reactive than hydrogen, displaces hydrogen from the acid). It is also exothermic.`,teacherTip:`Metal + dilute acid → salt + hydrogen gas (for metals above H in the reactivity series).`,examTip:`Add ↑ for an evolved gas and ↓ for a precipitate.`},

// ======================== CH6: CHEMICAL REACTIONS ========================
{id:"ch6n1",topicId:"chem-ch6",type:"note",subtopic:"Types of Chemical Reactions",content:`(1) COMBINATION (Synthesis): A + B → AB. Two/more substances combine into one. Example: 2Mg + O₂ → 2MgO; CaO + H₂O → Ca(OH)₂.\n(2) DECOMPOSITION: AB → A + B. One substance splits into two/more. Sub-types: thermal (heat, e.g. CaCO₃ → CaO + CO₂), electrolytic (electricity, 2H₂O → 2H₂ + O₂), photolytic (light, 2AgCl → 2Ag + Cl₂).\n(3) DISPLACEMENT: A + BC → AC + B. A more reactive element displaces a less reactive one. Example: Zn + CuSO₄ → ZnSO₄ + Cu.\n(4) DOUBLE DISPLACEMENT: AB + CD → AD + CB. Ions are exchanged; often forms a precipitate or neutralises. Example: NaCl + AgNO₃ → AgCl↓ + NaNO₃.`,explanation:`Combination = marriage. Decomposition = divorce. Displacement = one partner replaces another. Double displacement = partner swap.`,teacherTip:`Learn one example for each type — examiners always ask for examples.`,examTip:`Count reactants→products: 2→1 (combination), 1→2 (decomposition).`},
{id:"ch6n2",topicId:"chem-ch6",type:"note",subtopic:"Reactivity Series",content:`The REACTIVITY (activity) SERIES ranks metals from most to least reactive:\nK > Na > Ca > Mg > Al > Zn > Fe > Pb > (H) > Cu > Ag > Au > Pt.\nA more reactive metal DISPLACES a less reactive metal from its salt solution. Metals ABOVE hydrogen displace H₂ from dilute acids; metals BELOW (Cu, Ag, Au) do not. The series also predicts how vigorously a metal reacts with water/oxygen.`,explanation:`Potassium is the over-excited kid — reacts violently with almost everything. Gold is calm and barely reacts, which is why it never tarnishes.`,teacherTip:`Mnemonic: "Please Stop Calling Me A Zebra, I Like Hunting Cute Silver Gold Pets."`,examTip:`Hydrogen (H) is included to predict which metals react with dilute acids.`},
{id:"ch6n3",topicId:"chem-ch6",type:"note",subtopic:"NEET Bridge — Redox (Oxidation & Reduction)",content:`Many of these reactions are REDOX reactions — oxidation and reduction happen together. Class-8 view: OXIDATION = gain of oxygen / loss of hydrogen; REDUCTION = loss of oxygen / gain of hydrogen. NEET view: OXIDATION = LOSS of electrons; REDUCTION = GAIN of electrons (remember OIL RIG — Oxidation Is Loss, Reduction Is Gain). The substance that gets oxidised is the REDUCING agent; the one reduced is the OXIDISING agent. Example: Zn + CuSO₄ → ZnSO₄ + Cu — Zn is oxidised (loses electrons), Cu²⁺ is reduced (gains electrons).`,explanation:`Displacement reactions are really electron-transfer (redox) reactions. The reactivity series is essentially an "electron-losing tendency" ranking — exactly the electrochemical series you meet in NEET.`,teacherTip:`OIL RIG: Oxidation Is Loss, Reduction Is Gain (of electrons).`,examTip:`NEET: identify the oxidising agent (gets reduced) and reducing agent (gets oxidised).`},
// T/F
{id:"ch6tf1",topicId:"chem-ch6",type:"true_false",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"A more reactive metal can displace a less reactive metal from its salt solution.",correctAnswer:"true",answer:`True. For example, zinc (more reactive) displaces copper (less reactive) from copper sulphate solution: Zn + CuSO₄ → ZnSO₄ + Cu.`,teacherTip:`The stronger metal "kicks out" the weaker one.`,examTip:`Support with a specific displacement equation.`},
{id:"ch6tf2",topicId:"chem-ch6",type:"true_false",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"Copper can displace hydrogen from dilute hydrochloric acid.",correctAnswer:"false",answer:`False. Copper lies BELOW hydrogen in the reactivity series, so it cannot displace hydrogen from dilute acids; no reaction occurs. Only metals above H (Zn, Fe, Mg…) do.`,teacherTip:`Below H = no H₂ from acids.`,examTip:`Use the position relative to hydrogen to predict acid reactions.`},
// Fill blanks
{id:"ch6fb1",topicId:"chem-ch6",type:"fill_blank",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"Heating calcium carbonate to give calcium oxide and carbon dioxide is a ______ reaction.",blankAnswer:"decomposition",answer:`A (thermal) decomposition reaction: CaCO₃ → CaO + CO₂. One compound breaks into two on heating.`,teacherTip:`One → many = decomposition.`,examTip:`Specify the sub-type (thermal/electrolytic/photolytic) for full marks.`},
// MCQ
{id:"ch6mcq1",topicId:"chem-ch6",type:"mcq",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"2Mg + O₂ → 2MgO is an example of:",options:["Decomposition","Displacement","Combination","Double displacement"],correctOption:2,answer:`A combination reaction — two reactants (Mg and O₂) combine to form one product (MgO).`,teacherTip:`Two → one = combination.`,examTip:`Count reactants and products to classify quickly.`},
{id:"ch6mcq2",topicId:"chem-ch6",type:"mcq",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"In the reaction Zn + CuSO₄ → ZnSO₄ + Cu, which species is reduced?",options:["Zn","Cu²⁺","SO₄²⁻","Zn²⁺"],correctOption:1,answer:`Cu²⁺ is reduced — it gains electrons to become copper metal (Cu). Zn is oxidised (loses electrons). Remember OIL RIG: Reduction Is Gain of electrons.`,teacherTip:`The ion that turns into a neutral metal has gained electrons → reduced.`,examTip:`Reduction = gain of electrons; the reduced species is the oxidising agent.`},
// Assertion-Reason
{id:"ch6ar1",topicId:"chem-ch6",type:"mcq",subtopic:"Assertion–Reason",question:"Assertion (A): An iron nail dipped in copper sulphate solution turns brownish and the blue colour fades. Reason (R): Iron is more reactive than copper and displaces it from the solution.",options:["Both A and R are true, and R is the correct explanation of A","Both A and R are true, but R is NOT the correct explanation of A","A is true but R is false","A is false but R is true"],correctOption:0,answer:`Both true and R explains A. Fe + CuSO₄ → FeSO₄ + Cu: copper deposits on the nail (brown coat) and the blue Cu²⁺ is replaced by pale-green Fe²⁺, so the blue colour fades.`,teacherTip:`Blue (Cu²⁺) fading + brown coat = a displacement reaction.`,examTip:`Connect the colour change to the reactivity-series order.`},
// Short answer
{id:"ch6sa1",topicId:"chem-ch6",type:"short_answer",subtopic:"Short/Long Answer",question:"Explain the four types of chemical reactions with one example each.",answer:`1. COMBINATION: Two or more substances combine into one product.\n   2Na + Cl₂ → 2NaCl\n\n2. DECOMPOSITION: One substance breaks into two or more products.\n   2H₂O --electrolysis→ 2H₂ + O₂\n\n3. DISPLACEMENT: A more reactive element replaces a less reactive one.\n   Fe + CuSO₄ → FeSO₄ + Cu\n\n4. DOUBLE DISPLACEMENT: Two compounds exchange ions to form two new compounds.\n   NaCl + AgNO₃ → AgCl↓ + NaNO₃`,teacherTip:`Patterns: A+B→AB, AB→A+B, A+BC→AC+B, AB+CD→AD+CB.`,examTip:`Write a balanced equation for each type.`},
{id:"ch6sa2",topicId:"chem-ch6",type:"short_answer",subtopic:"HOTS / Application",question:"Silver chloride is kept in a coloured/dark bottle. Explain why, with reference to the type of reaction involved.",answer:`Silver chloride undergoes a PHOTOLYTIC DECOMPOSITION reaction in the presence of sunlight:\n\n2AgCl --sunlight→ 2Ag + Cl₂\n\nIt slowly turns grey because metallic silver is formed. To prevent this light-driven decomposition, AgCl (and AgBr) is stored in dark/amber bottles that block light.\n\nThis property is exactly what makes silver halides useful in traditional black-and-white photographic film.`,teacherTip:`Light-sensitive silver salts = photolytic decomposition.`,examTip:`Name the sub-type (photolytic) and give the equation.`},

// ======================== CH7: HYDROGEN ========================
{id:"ch7n1",topicId:"chem-ch7",type:"note",subtopic:"Hydrogen — Properties & Preparation",content:`HYDROGEN (H₂): the lightest element; colourless, odourless, tasteless gas; highly inflammable; burns with a pale-blue flame to form water; neutral to litmus; sparingly soluble in water. LAB PREPARATION: zinc + dilute hydrochloric acid (or dilute sulphuric acid): Zn + 2HCl → ZnCl₂ + H₂↑. (Granulated zinc is preferred; very pure/very dilute acid reacts too slowly, so impure zinc speeds it up.) COLLECTION: by downward displacement of water (it is insoluble) or upward displacement of air (it is much lighter than air). TEST: a burning splint gives a "pop" sound.`,explanation:`Hydrogen is the simplest, lightest element; its name means "water-former" because burning it produces water.`,teacherTip:`"Hydro" = water, "gen" = producer.`,examTip:`State the preparation EQUATION, the collection method AND the pop test.`},
{id:"ch7n2",topicId:"chem-ch7",type:"note",subtopic:"Uses of Hydrogen",content:`Uses: (1) FUEL — hydrogen fuel cells give clean energy (only product is water); also has the highest calorific value of any fuel. (2) HYDROGENATION — converting unsaturated vegetable oils into solid fats/vanaspati ghee using a nickel catalyst. (3) MANUFACTURE OF AMMONIA via the Haber process: N₂ + 3H₂ ⇌ 2NH₃ (used to make fertilisers). (4) Making methanol and hydrochloric acid. (5) Oxy-hydrogen flame for welding/cutting metals. (6) ROCKET FUEL (liquid hydrogen).`,explanation:`Hydrogen is the "fuel of the future" — when it burns the only waste product is water, so there is no pollution.`,teacherTip:`Hydrogen fuel cell: 2H₂ + O₂ → 2H₂O + energy. Clean and green!`,examTip:`List at least 4 uses with a one-line reason for each.`},
{id:"ch7n3",topicId:"chem-ch7",type:"note",subtopic:"NEET Bridge — The Unique Position of Hydrogen",content:`Hydrogen is special: with 1 valence electron it resembles GROUP 1 (alkali metals — can lose 1 e⁻ to form H⁺), yet needing 1 electron to fill its shell it also resembles GROUP 17 (halogens — can gain 1 e⁻ to form H⁻, the hydride ion). So in the periodic table its placement is debated. In NEET you meet its isotopes (protium, deuterium, tritium), heavy water (D₂O, a moderator in nuclear reactors), and hydrogen as the best green fuel by mass. The Haber process you learn here is a core equilibrium example in Class 11/12.`,explanation:`Hydrogen behaves like both a metal (forming H⁺) and a non-metal (forming H⁻), which is why it doesn't fit neatly in one group.`,teacherTip:`H⁺ = metal-like; H⁻ (hydride) = halogen-like.`,examTip:`NEET: D₂O = heavy water = neutron moderator; the highest calorific value fuel is H₂.`},
// T/F
{id:"ch7tf1",topicId:"chem-ch7",type:"true_false",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"Hydrogen is heavier than air.",correctAnswer:"false",answer:`False. Hydrogen is the LIGHTEST gas — about 14.4 times lighter than air — which is why it can be collected by upward displacement of air.`,teacherTip:`Lightest element of all; it rises.`,examTip:`Link its low density to "upward displacement of air" collection.`},
{id:"ch7tf2",topicId:"chem-ch7",type:"true_false",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"Hydrogen turns moist blue litmus red.",correctAnswer:"false",answer:`False. Hydrogen is NEUTRAL to litmus — it changes neither blue nor red litmus, since it is neither acidic nor basic.`,teacherTip:`H₂ is a neutral gas.`,examTip:`Contrast with CO₂ (weakly acidic) which turns blue litmus faintly red.`},
// Fill blanks
{id:"ch7fb1",topicId:"chem-ch7",type:"fill_blank",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"Hydrogen burns in air with a characteristic ______ sound when tested with a burning splint.",blankAnswer:"pop",answer:`A "pop" sound — the standard confirmatory test for hydrogen gas.`,teacherTip:`Pop test = hydrogen confirmed.`,examTip:`Name the test AND its result.`},
// MCQ
{id:"ch7mcq1",topicId:"chem-ch7",type:"mcq",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"Hydrogen is prepared in the lab by reacting zinc with:",options:["Water","Dilute HCl","Concentrated nitric acid","Oxygen"],correctOption:1,answer:`Dilute hydrochloric acid: Zn + 2HCl → ZnCl₂ + H₂↑. (Concentrated/nitric acid is avoided because HNO₃ is a strong oxidiser and gives oxides of nitrogen instead of hydrogen.)`,teacherTip:`Zinc + dilute non-oxidising acid = salt + hydrogen.`,examTip:`Note WHY nitric acid is not used (it oxidises the H₂).`},
{id:"ch7mcq2",topicId:"chem-ch7",type:"mcq",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"The conversion of vegetable oil into vanaspati ghee using hydrogen is called:",options:["Hydration","Hydrogenation","Hydrolysis","Dehydration"],correctOption:1,answer:`Hydrogenation — adding hydrogen across the C=C double bonds of unsaturated oils (using a nickel catalyst) to make a solid saturated fat.`,teacherTip:`Adding H₂ to oils = hydrogenation.`,examTip:`Mention the nickel catalyst for full marks.`},
// Assertion-Reason
{id:"ch7ar1",topicId:"chem-ch7",type:"mcq",subtopic:"Assertion–Reason",question:"Assertion (A): Hydrogen can be collected by the downward displacement of water. Reason (R): Hydrogen is highly soluble in water.",options:["Both A and R are true, and R is the correct explanation of A","Both A and R are true, but R is NOT the correct explanation of A","A is true but R is false","A is false but R is true"],correctOption:2,answer:`A is true but R is false. Hydrogen IS collected over water, but precisely because it is almost INSOLUBLE in water (not soluble). A soluble gas could not be collected this way.`,teacherTip:`Gases collected over water must be insoluble in it.`,examTip:`A gas soluble in water (e.g. NH₃, HCl) cannot be collected over water.`},
// Short answer
{id:"ch7sa1",topicId:"chem-ch7",type:"short_answer",subtopic:"Short/Long Answer",question:"Describe the laboratory preparation of hydrogen gas. How is it collected and tested?",answer:`PREPARATION: Granulated zinc is taken in a flask fitted with a thistle funnel and delivery tube. Dilute hydrochloric acid is added through the thistle funnel.\n\nReaction: Zn + 2HCl → ZnCl₂ + H₂↑\n\nCOLLECTION:\n1. Downward displacement of water — because H₂ is insoluble in water.\n2. Upward displacement of air — because H₂ is much lighter than air.\n\nTEST: Bring a burning splint to the mouth of the gas jar — hydrogen burns with a "pop" sound, confirming its presence.`,teacherTip:`The "pop" test is the standard test for hydrogen.`,examTip:`Cover apparatus, reaction, collection AND test for a complete answer.`},
{id:"ch7sa2",topicId:"chem-ch7",type:"short_answer",subtopic:"HOTS / Application",question:"Hydrogen is described as the cleanest fuel, yet hydrogen-filled balloons were replaced by helium. Explain both statements.",answer:`CLEANEST FUEL: When hydrogen burns it combines with oxygen to give only water vapour (2H₂ + O₂ → 2H₂O + energy). There is no carbon dioxide, soot or smoke, so it causes no air pollution, and it has the highest calorific value of any fuel.\n\nWHY REPLACED BY HELIUM IN BALLOONS: Hydrogen is extremely INFLAMMABLE — it forms an explosive mixture with air and can ignite from a tiny spark (as in the Hindenburg disaster). Helium is also lighter than air but is INERT (does not burn), so it is far safer for filling balloons and airships despite providing slightly less lift.\n\nThus hydrogen's reactivity is an advantage as a fuel but a danger in balloons.`,teacherTip:`Same property (combustibility) is a virtue in a fuel and a hazard in a balloon.`,examTip:`Contrast "inflammable H₂" with "inert He".`},

// ======================== CH8: WATER ========================
{id:"ch8n1",topicId:"chem-ch8",type:"note",subtopic:"Water — Properties and Composition",content:`Water (H₂O) is a compound of hydrogen and oxygen combined in the ratio 2:1 by VOLUME (1:8 by MASS). It is the UNIVERSAL SOLVENT (dissolves more substances than any other liquid). Boiling point = 100°C, freezing point = 0°C (at 1 atm). It shows ANOMALOUS EXPANSION: between 4°C and 0°C it EXPANDS on cooling, so ice is less dense than water and floats; water has maximum density at 4°C. Water exists in all three states in nature (ice, water, vapour).`,explanation:`Water is the universal solvent because its polar molecules dissolve a huge range of substances — vital for life, since nutrients dissolve in water to reach cells. Its anomalous expansion means ponds freeze top-down, protecting aquatic life below.`,teacherTip:`Maximum density of water is at 4°C, not 0°C.`,examTip:`Explain WHY ice floating matters (insulates and protects aquatic life beneath).`},
{id:"ch8n2",topicId:"chem-ch8",type:"note",subtopic:"Hard and Soft Water",content:`SOFT WATER: lathers easily with soap; contains no (or little) dissolved calcium/magnesium salts. Examples: rainwater, distilled water.\nHARD WATER: does not lather easily and forms a white SCUM with soap; contains dissolved Ca²⁺ or Mg²⁺ salts.\nTEMPORARY hardness: caused by bicarbonates — Ca(HCO₃)₂, Mg(HCO₃)₂. Removed by BOILING (Clark's method uses slaked lime).\nPERMANENT hardness: caused by sulphates and chlorides — CaSO₄, MgCl₂, MgSO₄. Removed by adding washing soda (Na₂CO₃) or by ion-exchange (permutit/zeolite) methods.`,explanation:`Hard water wastes soap because Ca²⁺/Mg²⁺ ions react with soap to form an insoluble scum instead of lather. Detergents work even in hard water because their calcium salts are soluble.`,teacherTip:`Temporary = boiling fixes it. Permanent = needs chemicals (washing soda).`,examTip:`Know the salts causing each type AND the removal method for each.`},
{id:"ch8n3",topicId:"chem-ch8",type:"note",subtopic:"Water Purification",content:`Methods: (1) FILTRATION — removes suspended impurities. (2) SEDIMENTATION & DECANTATION — heavy particles settle and clear water is poured off (alum/flocculation speeds this). (3) BOILING — kills bacteria and viruses (simplest home method). (4) CHLORINATION — adding chlorine/bleaching powder to kill germs. (5) DISTILLATION — evaporation + condensation gives the PUREST water (removes dissolved salts AND microbes). (6) REVERSE OSMOSIS (RO) — forces water through a semi-permeable membrane to remove dissolved salts (used for desalination). (7) UV treatment — kills microorganisms.`,explanation:`Each method targets different impurities; municipal supplies usually combine several (sedimentation → filtration → chlorination).`,teacherTip:`Distilled water is purest but tasteless (no dissolved minerals).`,examTip:`State at least 3 methods AND the type of impurity each removes.`},
{id:"ch8n4",topicId:"chem-ch8",type:"note",subtopic:"NEET Bridge — Polarity, H-Bonding & the Water Cycle",content:`Water's amazing properties come from its bent shape and POLAR O–H bonds, which let molecules form HYDROGEN BONDS with each other. These explain its high boiling point, high specific/latent heat, surface tension and its power as a solvent (key for biology in NEET). In living systems, water is the medium for all reactions, the reactant in PHOTOSYNTHESIS (6CO₂ + 6H₂O → C₆H₁₂O₆ + 6O₂) and a product of RESPIRATION. The natural WATER CYCLE (evaporation → condensation → precipitation) is a giant continuous distillation driven by the Sun.`,explanation:`Hydrogen bonding is the single idea that ties together water's high boiling point, its solvent power and ice floating — all of which matter for life and for NEET biology/chemistry.`,teacherTip:`Polar molecule + hydrogen bonding = water's "superpowers".`,examTip:`NEET: link water's polarity to its role as biological solvent and to photosynthesis/respiration.`},
// T/F
{id:"ch8tf1",topicId:"chem-ch8",type:"true_false",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"Hard water lathers easily with soap.",correctAnswer:"false",answer:`False. SOFT water lathers easily. Hard water does NOT lather because dissolved Ca²⁺/Mg²⁺ ions react with soap to form an insoluble scum.`,teacherTip:`Hard water = hard to lather. The name is the clue.`,examTip:`Explain the chemistry: Ca²⁺/Mg²⁺ + soap → scum.`},
{id:"ch8tf2",topicId:"chem-ch8",type:"true_false",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"Water has its maximum density at 0°C.",correctAnswer:"false",answer:`False. Water has its MAXIMUM density at 4°C. Below 4°C it expands again (anomalous expansion), so 0°C ice is less dense and floats.`,teacherTip:`4°C is the special "densest" temperature of water.`,examTip:`This anomalous expansion is why ice floats and aquatic life survives winter.`},
// Fill blanks
{id:"ch8fb1",topicId:"chem-ch8",type:"fill_blank",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"Temporary hardness of water is caused by ______ salts.",blankAnswer:"bicarbonate",answer:`Temporary hardness is caused by dissolved bicarbonates of calcium and magnesium — Ca(HCO₃)₂ and Mg(HCO₃)₂ — and is removed by boiling.`,teacherTip:`Bicarbonate = temporary; sulphate/chloride = permanent.`,examTip:`Write the formula Ca(HCO₃)₂ for precision.`},
{id:"ch8fb2",topicId:"chem-ch8",type:"fill_blank",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"Permanent hardness can be removed by adding ______ soda.",blankAnswer:"washing",answer:`Washing soda (sodium carbonate, Na₂CO₃) precipitates Ca²⁺/Mg²⁺ as insoluble carbonates, softening permanently hard water.`,teacherTip:`Washing soda removes BOTH temporary and permanent hardness.`,examTip:`Give the chemical name and formula: sodium carbonate, Na₂CO₃.`},
// MCQ
{id:"ch8mcq1",topicId:"chem-ch8",type:"mcq",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"Which method gives the purest form of water?",options:["Filtration","Boiling","Chlorination","Distillation"],correctOption:3,answer:`Distillation — by evaporating and re-condensing, it removes dissolved salts, microbes and all impurities, giving the purest water.`,teacherTip:`Distilled water = lab-grade pure; used in batteries and experiments.`,examTip:`Distillation removes BOTH suspended AND dissolved impurities.`},
{id:"ch8mcq2",topicId:"chem-ch8",type:"mcq",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"Temporary hardness of water is removed by:",options:["Adding common salt","Boiling","Filtration","Adding more soap"],correctOption:1,answer:`Boiling — it decomposes soluble bicarbonates into insoluble carbonates that settle out, removing temporary hardness.`,teacherTip:`Boiling fixes temporary hardness only.`,examTip:`For permanent hardness you need washing soda, not boiling.`},
// Assertion-Reason
{id:"ch8ar1",topicId:"chem-ch8",type:"mcq",subtopic:"Assertion–Reason",question:"Assertion (A): Ice floats on water. Reason (R): Ice is less dense than water because water expands on freezing (anomalous expansion).",options:["Both A and R are true, and R is the correct explanation of A","Both A and R are true, but R is NOT the correct explanation of A","A is true but R is false","A is false but R is true"],correctOption:0,answer:`Both true and R explains A. Water expands as it freezes, so ice has a lower density than liquid water and therefore floats.`,teacherTip:`Lower density = floats; the cause is anomalous expansion.`,examTip:`Mention maximum density at 4°C as supporting detail.`},
// Short answer
{id:"ch8sa1",topicId:"chem-ch8",type:"short_answer",subtopic:"Short/Long Answer",question:"Differentiate between hard water and soft water. How can each type of hardness be removed?",answer:`SOFT WATER: Lathers easily with soap; free from Ca²⁺/Mg²⁺ salts. Examples: rainwater, distilled water.\n\nHARD WATER: Does not lather, forms scum with soap; contains dissolved Ca²⁺/Mg²⁺ salts.\n\nRemoving hardness:\n1. TEMPORARY HARDNESS (bicarbonates): removed by BOILING — bicarbonates decompose into insoluble carbonates that settle. (Clark's method uses slaked lime.)\n2. PERMANENT HARDNESS (sulphates/chlorides): removed by adding WASHING SODA (Na₂CO₃), which precipitates the Ca/Mg ions as insoluble carbonates; ion-exchange (zeolite) methods also work.`,teacherTip:`Boiling → temporary only; washing soda → both types.`,examTip:`Name the specific salts causing each type of hardness.`},
{id:"ch8sa2",topicId:"chem-ch8",type:"short_answer",subtopic:"HOTS / Application",question:"Why is water called the 'universal solvent', and why is this property important for living organisms?",answer:`Water is called the universal solvent because it dissolves a greater variety of substances than any other common liquid. This is due to its POLAR molecules: the slightly positive H ends and slightly negative O end attract and surround the ions/molecules of many solids, liquids and gases, pulling them into solution.\n\nImportance for life:\n• Nutrients, minerals and gases (O₂, CO₂) dissolve in water and are transported through blood and sap to cells.\n• Digestion and most cellular chemical reactions occur in aqueous (water) medium.\n• Waste products are dissolved and removed (e.g. in urine).\n\nThus water's solvent power makes it the medium of life.`,teacherTip:`"Universal solvent" comes from water's polarity.`,examTip:`Link polarity → solvent power → biological transport and reactions.`},

// ======================== CH9: CARBON AND ITS COMPOUNDS ========================
{id:"ch9n1",topicId:"chem-ch9",type:"note",subtopic:"Carbon — Allotropes",content:`Carbon exists in different forms called ALLOTROPES — same element, different structures and properties:\n(1) DIAMOND — hardest natural substance; each C bonded to 4 others in a rigid 3-D tetrahedral network; no free electrons so it is a non-conductor; transparent; used in cutting/drilling and jewellery.\n(2) GRAPHITE — soft, black, slippery; each C bonded to 3 others in flat hexagonal layers held by weak forces (layers slide); has free electrons so it CONDUCTS electricity; used in pencils, lubricants and electrodes.\n(3) FULLERENE (Buckminsterfullerene C₆₀, "buckyball") — cage-like spherical molecule; CARBON NANOTUBES and GRAPHENE are related modern allotropes.\nAll are pure carbon but have vastly different properties.`,explanation:`Diamond and graphite are both 100% carbon, yet one is the hardest substance and the other one of the softest — the difference is purely how the atoms are arranged.`,teacherTip:`Same atoms, different arrangement = different properties. That is allotropy.`,examTip:`Compare diamond and graphite on hardness, conductivity, structure and uses.`},
{id:"ch9n2",topicId:"chem-ch9",type:"note",subtopic:"Carbon Compounds & Catenation",content:`Carbon forms an enormous number of compounds (millions) for two reasons: (1) it is TETRAVALENT (valency 4 — forms 4 strong covalent bonds), and (2) CATENATION — the unique ability to bond with other carbon atoms to form long chains, branches and rings. Key compounds: (1) CO₂ — exhaled in respiration, used in photosynthesis, a greenhouse gas. (2) CO — poisonous, colourless, odourless, from INCOMPLETE combustion; binds to haemoglobin. (3) CH₄ (methane) — simplest hydrocarbon, main component of natural gas/biogas. (4) C₂H₅OH (ethanol) — alcohol, also a biofuel.`,explanation:`Carbon is the "Lego king" of chemistry — tetravalency plus catenation let it build the vast world of organic molecules that make up all living things.`,teacherTip:`Catenation + tetravalency = the basis of organic chemistry.`,examTip:`Know formula, one property and one use for CO₂, CO and CH₄.`},
{id:"ch9n3",topicId:"chem-ch9",type:"note",subtopic:"CO₂ — Properties and Test",content:`Carbon dioxide (CO₂): colourless, odourless gas; about 1.5 times heavier than air; does NOT support combustion (extinguishes fire); weakly acidic (turns moist blue litmus faintly red, forming carbonic acid H₂CO₃). LIME-WATER TEST (the standard test for CO₂): CO₂ turns lime water milky — CO₂ + Ca(OH)₂ → CaCO₃↓ + H₂O. On passing EXCESS CO₂ the milkiness disappears as soluble calcium bicarbonate forms: CaCO₃ + CO₂ + H₂O → Ca(HCO₃)₂. Sources: burning fuels, respiration, fermentation. Uses: fire extinguishers, fizzy drinks, photosynthesis, dry ice (refrigerant).`,explanation:`CO₂ acts like a fire blanket — being denser than air and non-combustible, it settles over flames and cuts off oxygen. The lime-water test is the definitive chemical test for CO₂.`,teacherTip:`Lime water clear → milky = CO₂; excess CO₂ makes it clear again.`,examTip:`The lime-water test (and the "excess CO₂" reversal) is one of the most-asked points.`},
{id:"ch9n4",topicId:"chem-ch9",type:"note",subtopic:"NEET Bridge — Hydrocarbons & Functional Groups",content:`The CH₄/C₂H₅OH you meet here open into ORGANIC CHEMISTRY, a huge NEET topic. Carbon compounds are classified by FUNCTIONAL GROUP: alkanes (single bonds, C–C, "saturated"), alkenes (C=C), alkynes (C≡C), alcohols (–OH), carboxylic acids (–COOH), etc. Saturated hydrocarbons burn with a clean blue flame; unsaturated ones with a sooty yellow flame (more carbon). The COMPLETE combustion of a hydrocarbon gives CO₂ + H₂O; INCOMPLETE combustion (limited O₂) gives poisonous CO + soot — the reason for ventilation around heaters.`,explanation:`Just two ideas — tetravalency and catenation — generate the entire branching tree of organic chemistry that dominates NEET. Recognising functional groups is the first step.`,teacherTip:`Blue flame = complete combustion (enough O₂); yellow/sooty = incomplete.`,examTip:`NEET: complete combustion → CO₂ + H₂O; incomplete → CO + C (soot).`},
// T/F
{id:"ch9tf1",topicId:"chem-ch9",type:"true_false",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"Diamond and graphite are allotropes of carbon.",correctAnswer:"true",answer:`True. Both are made entirely of carbon atoms but have different structural arrangements, giving them very different physical properties.`,teacherTip:`Allotropes = same element, different forms.`,examTip:`Name 3 differences between diamond and graphite.`},
{id:"ch9tf2",topicId:"chem-ch9",type:"true_false",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"Carbon dioxide supports combustion.",correctAnswer:"false",answer:`False. CO₂ does NOT support combustion; it extinguishes fire, which is why it is used in fire extinguishers (it is also denser than air, so it settles over the flame).`,teacherTip:`CO₂ smothers fire by cutting off oxygen.`,examTip:`Mention that CO₂ is denser than air, so it blankets the fire.`},
{id:"ch9tf3",topicId:"chem-ch9",type:"true_false",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"Graphite conducts electricity but diamond does not.",correctAnswer:"true",answer:`True. In graphite each carbon uses only 3 of its 4 bonds, leaving free (delocalised) electrons that carry current. In diamond all 4 electrons are locked in bonds, so there are no free electrons and it cannot conduct.`,teacherTip:`Free electrons in graphite = conductivity; none in diamond.`,examTip:`Explain conductivity using the bonding (3 bonds vs 4 bonds).`},
// Fill blanks
{id:"ch9fb1",topicId:"chem-ch9",type:"fill_blank",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"Carbon dioxide turns lime water ______.",blankAnswer:"milky",answer:`CO₂ + Ca(OH)₂ → CaCO₃↓ (white precipitate) + H₂O. The insoluble calcium carbonate makes lime water look milky/cloudy.`,teacherTip:`Milky = a white precipitate of CaCO₃.`,examTip:`Write the full equation — it is almost always asked with this fact.`},
{id:"ch9fb2",topicId:"chem-ch9",type:"fill_blank",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"The ability of carbon atoms to link together to form long chains is called ______.",blankAnswer:"catenation",answer:`Catenation — the self-linking of carbon atoms into chains, branches and rings, which (with tetravalency) is why carbon forms millions of compounds.`,teacherTip:`Catena = chain.`,examTip:`Pair "catenation" with "tetravalency" when explaining carbon's versatility.`},
// MCQ
{id:"ch9mcq1",topicId:"chem-ch9",type:"mcq",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"Which allotrope of carbon is the hardest natural substance?",options:["Graphite","Fullerene","Diamond","Charcoal"],correctOption:2,answer:`Diamond — each carbon is bonded to 4 others in a rigid 3-D tetrahedral network, making it extremely hard.`,teacherTip:`4 bonds in all directions = unbreakable network.`,examTip:`Give the structural reason (3-D tetrahedral bonding) for diamond's hardness.`},
{id:"ch9mcq2",topicId:"chem-ch9",type:"mcq",subtopic:"Objective Questions",question:"Incomplete combustion of carbon fuels is dangerous mainly because it produces:",options:["Carbon dioxide","Water vapour","Carbon monoxide","Oxygen"],correctOption:2,answer:`Carbon monoxide (CO) — a colourless, odourless, poisonous gas formed when fuel burns in a limited supply of oxygen. It binds strongly to haemoglobin and can be fatal, which is why heaters need ventilation.`,teacherTip:`Limited O₂ → CO (poison) instead of CO₂.`,examTip:`State that CO is poisonous because it binds to haemoglobin.`},
// Assertion-Reason
{id:"ch9ar1",topicId:"chem-ch9",type:"mcq",subtopic:"Assertion–Reason",question:"Assertion (A): When excess carbon dioxide is passed through lime water, the milkiness disappears. Reason (R): Insoluble calcium carbonate reacts with excess CO₂ and water to form soluble calcium bicarbonate.",options:["Both A and R are true, and R is the correct explanation of A","Both A and R are true, but R is NOT the correct explanation of A","A is true but R is false","A is false but R is true"],correctOption:0,answer:`Both true and R explains A. First CO₂ + Ca(OH)₂ → CaCO₃↓ + H₂O (milky); then with excess CO₂: CaCO₃ + CO₂ + H₂O → Ca(HCO₃)₂ (soluble), so the milkiness clears.`,teacherTip:`Milky then clear = the excess-CO₂ effect.`,examTip:`Write BOTH equations to explain the two-stage observation.`},
// Short answer
{id:"ch9sa1",topicId:"chem-ch9",type:"short_answer",subtopic:"Short/Long Answer",question:"Compare diamond and graphite. Why do they have such different properties despite being the same element?",answer:`Both diamond and graphite are allotropes of carbon (100% carbon) but differ in structure:\n\nDIAMOND:\n• Each C bonded to 4 others (tetrahedral)\n• Rigid 3-D network\n• Hardest natural substance\n• Does NOT conduct electricity (no free electrons)\n• Transparent, lustrous\n• Used in cutting tools, drilling, jewellery\n\nGRAPHITE:\n• Each C bonded to 3 others (flat hexagonal layers)\n• Layers held by weak forces and slide easily (soft, slippery)\n• Good conductor of electricity (free electrons between layers)\n• Black, opaque\n• Used in pencils, lubricants, electrodes\n\nReason: the ARRANGEMENT/bonding of the carbon atoms differs, even though the atoms are identical — structure determines properties.`,teacherTip:`Structure determines properties. Same atoms ≠ same properties if arranged differently.`,examTip:`Compare at least 5 properties AND give the structural reason.`},
{id:"ch9sa2",topicId:"chem-ch9",type:"short_answer",subtopic:"HOTS / Application",question:"A gas stove flame turns yellow and leaves black soot on vessels, instead of burning blue. Explain what is happening and how to fix it.",answer:`A clean blue flame indicates COMPLETE combustion — there is enough oxygen, and the fuel burns fully to CO₂ + H₂O, releasing maximum heat.\n\nA yellow, sooty flame indicates INCOMPLETE combustion — the air (oxygen) supply is insufficient. The fuel does not burn fully, so it produces unburnt carbon (the black soot) and poisonous carbon monoxide (CO), and gives less heat. Soot also dirties the vessels.\n\nFIX: increase the air supply by opening/cleaning the air holes (the air inlet) at the base of the burner so more oxygen mixes with the gas. The flame should then turn blue again.\n\nThis also matters for safety, because incomplete combustion releases poisonous CO.`,teacherTip:`Yellow + soot = not enough air; open the air holes.`,examTip:`Link blue↔complete (CO₂) and yellow↔incomplete (CO + soot), and note the CO hazard.`},
];
